"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709344","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>This information is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>Such information as is available is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>The data in the table is for adults only and is only for the inpatient activity related to their care. It does not include any potential costs incurred for follow-up treatments such as rehabilitation or future outpatient appointments. Additionally, the data available is for the whole of the National Health Service in England and is not broken down by clinical commissioning group.</p><p> </p><p>The data source for the table is from reference costs, which are the average unit costs to NHS trusts and NHS foundation trusts of providing defined services in a given financial year to NHS patients. Reference costs for acute care are collected by healthcare resource group, which are standard groupings of clinically similar treatments which use common levels of healthcare resource.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the total cost, in millions, to the NHS of inpatient stays for heart failure from 2013-14 to 2015-16.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>£ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>259</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>276</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>309</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: </em>Department of Health Reference Costs.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-15T16:05:05.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709344/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709344/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Heart Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of heart failure to (a) the NHS and (b) Ealing Clinical Commissioning Group in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","67163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709345","Department for Education","false","2017-03-15","<p>Exemptions from the Immigration Skills Charge for employers were announced on 24 March 2016. These include exemptions for employers of specified occupations skilled to PhD level and individuals switching from a Tier 4 student visa to Tier 2 (General). All employers, including the NHS, who recruit workers through the Tier 2 skilled worker route will benefit from these exemptions.</p><p> </p><p>We have not estimated the potential annual cost of the charge to providers. The cost will depend on employer use of the Tier 2 skilled worker route. The Government has no plans to reimburse the cost of the Immigration Skills Charge for any employer.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","66866 ; 66867","2017-03-15T16:51:18.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709345/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709345/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-08","NHS: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the Government plans to support the NHS to mitigate the financial cost of the immigration skills charge for financial year 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","67154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709346","Department of Health","false","2017-03-16","<p>The Department is currently considering options for a consultation on the regulation of Physician Associates, which will be published in due course.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-16T15:18:18.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709346/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709346/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Physician Associates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when his Department plans to publish the consultation on regulation of Physician Associates.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","67164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709347","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>In November 2016, NHS Improvement announced Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust as the preferred future provider of Liverpool Community Health NHS Trust's Liverpool services. This was subject to NHS Improvement undertaking detailed financial and regulatory checks on both Trusts’ plans before confirming the new arrangements ahead of a start date of 1 July 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Full business cases for such transactions, which may contain commercially sensitive information, are not usually published by NHS Improvement.</p><p> </p><p>On 7 February 2017, NHS Improvement announced it was pausing plans to transfer services from Liverpool Community Health NHS Trust to Bridgewater Community NHS Foundation Trust in order to perform additional evaluation of plans to transfer services.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:31:44.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709347/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709347/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on what date his Department expects Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust to publish its full business case in relation to the Liverpool community health service contract.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","67136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709348","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Sustainability and Transformation Fund revenue allocations for 2017/18 remain unchanged and will be allocated in line with the operating plans guidance for 2017/19 published in September 2016.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:36:22.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709348/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709348/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what criteria Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust will have to meet to be able to access an increased Sustainability and Transformation Fund allocation.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","67137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709349","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>Individual National Health Service organisations are responsible for ensuring their current rating assessments are correct, challenging them if necessary and seeking transitional relief. The Department does not routinely collect data from NHS organisations on their business rate charges in order to make an overall national assessment of changes. Business rate changes will be reflected in individual organisation financial plans. We expect plans to balance within the overall NHS budget, and to continue to deliver patient services in line with the objectives of the NHS England Mandate.</p><p> </p><p>An existing Government transitional relief scheme provides £3.6 billion of support for the minority of properties which face an increase in rates as a result of the 2017 revaluation, and applies equally to public bodies such as the NHS.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","67130","2017-03-13T17:41:03.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709349/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709349/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 64314, on NHS: finance, if the Government will make it its policy to give NHS bodies priority access to transitional relief funds.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","67134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709350","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>Individual National Health Service organisations are responsible for ensuring their current rating assessments are correct, challenging them if necessary and seeking transitional relief. The Department does not routinely collect data from NHS organisations on their business rate charges in order to make an overall national assessment of changes. Business rate changes will be reflected in individual organisation financial plans. We expect plans to balance within the overall NHS budget, and to continue to deliver patient services in line with the objectives of the NHS England Mandate.</p><p> </p><p>An existing Government transitional relief scheme provides £3.6 billion of support for the minority of properties which face an increase in rates as a result of the 2017 revaluation, and applies equally to public bodies such as the NHS.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","67134","2017-03-13T17:41:03.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709350/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709350/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","NHS: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 64314, on NHS: finance, if he will make an assessment of (a) the total annual cost of proposed business rates changes to the NHS and (b) the potential effect of those costs on the delivery of patient services.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","67130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709352","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>It is for the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) to provide national clinical guidance and advice, based on best evidence of clinical and cost effectiveness, for use of interventions, technology and devices.</p><p> </p><p>NICE has published a clinical guideline on the identification, assessment and management of obesity that contains recommendations for assessment for bariatric surgery to be considered for people with recent-onset type 2 diabetes within specified criteria:</p><p><a href="https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg189/chapter/1-recommendations" target="_blank">https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg189/chapter/1-recommendations</a></p><p> </p><p>It has not, however, published guidance on the specific role of bariatric surgery as an intervention to prevent type 2 diabetes in those at high risk.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-15T12:00:59.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709352/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709352/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the (a) clinical and (b) cost effectiveness of the provision of bariatric surgery alongside other preventative public health measures in reducing cases of type two diabetes.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","67004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709354","Department of Health","false","2017-03-16","<p>The following International Classification of Diseases codes classify a birth related brain injury:</p><p>- P10 Intracranial laceration and haemorrhage due to birth injury</p><p>- P11.0 Cerebral oedema due to birth injury</p><p>- P11.1 Other specified brain damage due to birth injury</p><p>- P11.2 Unspecified brain damage due to birth injury.</p><p>The available information is in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Birth episodes</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>539</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>605</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>324</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>155</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>91</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>77</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Hospital Episode Statistics</p><p>Note:</p><p> </p><p>Changes to the figures over time need to be interpreted in the context of improvements in data quality and coverage, improvements in coverage of independent sector activity and changes in National Health Service practice.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-16T15:14:52.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709354/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709354/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Brain: Injuries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many brain injuries around birth there were in (a) 2011, (b) 2012, (c) 2013, (d) 2014 and (e) 2015.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","67002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709355","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>Section 14Z2 of the Health and Social Care Act 2006 (as amended in 2012) places a duty on clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to involve and consult the public.</p><p> </p><p>Duties under this include the duty to include individuals when developing or changing services, including a statement of principles in their constitution and having regard to any guidance on consultation published by NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>If a CCG is failing to meet its functions, NHS England is able to issue directions to them, setting out what action it should take.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-15T13:46:26.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709355/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709355/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Clinical Commissioning Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will review the powers of clinical commissioning groups to make them more accountable to the public.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","66999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709356","Department of Health","false","2017-03-14","<p>The decision of the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) to fine Pfizer and Flynn Pharma is currently under appeal. As with other fine income, fines levied by the CMA for breaches of competition law are returned to the Consolidated Fund. Receipts from this fine will therefore help fund the £10 billion increase in National Health Service funding set out at the Spending Review. A separate process is available for the Secretary of State for Health to recover damages suffered as a result of this case through the courts. This money would flow back to the NHS for the benefit of patients, based on clinical priorities.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-14T10:53:01.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709356/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709356/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Epilepsy: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the Government is able to allocate Competition and Markets Authority fines collected from pharmaceutical manufacturers Pfizer and distributor Flynn Pharma for the purposes of research and treatment for epilepsy patients.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","66984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709357","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>It is the responsibility of employers to ensure their staff are suitably trained and appropriately supported to undertake the roles for which they are employed.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Quality Commission’s Fundamental Standards include a regulation on staffing which ensures that suitably qualified, competent, skilled persons must be deployed.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-15T15:52:28.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709357/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709357/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Carers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what duty is on local authorities to ensure that home care agencies provide mandatory bowel and bladder training for carers.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","66985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709358","Department of Health","false","2017-03-16","<p>Standards for United Kingdom online pharmacy services are the responsibility of the relevant professional regulatory bodies. These are the General Pharmaceutical Council and the Pharmaceutical Society of Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency is working with the General Medical Council, the General Pharmaceutical Council and the Care Quality Commission to monitor issues arising from online services. The four regulatory bodies issued a joint statement on 3 March stressing that providers and healthcare professionals working for online services must provide safe and effective care, including following professional guidelines on this matter. The Department is aware and supportive of this important work.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-16T15:44:08.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709358/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709358/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Pharmacy: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the study published by Oxford Academic on 17 February 2017 on inappropriate checks undertaken by online pharmacies, if he will discuss with the Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency means to prevent the online sale of antibiotics and other medicines without appropriate checks.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","66981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709359","Department of Health","false","2017-03-16","<p>The Healthcare Quality Improvement Partnership (HQIP) commissions, develops and manages the National Clinical Audit and Patient Outcomes Programme (NCAPOP), on behalf of NHS England, Wales and other devolved administrations. The programme currently consists of over 30 national clinical audits, six clinical outcome review programmes and the National Joint Registry. The Sentinel Stroke National Audit Programme is one of the NCAPOP topics.</p><p> </p><p>Patient Reported Experience Measures and Patient Reported Outcome Measures are not routinely commissioned through the NCAPOP.</p><p> </p><p>The design of the clinical audit is a matter for HQIP on behalf of NHS England and the Royal College of Physicians.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-16T10:29:06.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709359/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709359/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Strokes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 22 November 2016 to Question 53151, if the Government will ensure that the Sentinel Stroke National Audit Programme begins to collect data on patient experience and outcomes.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","66988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709360","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>NHS Property Services has 3,047 people who perform front-line National Health Service duties, such as cleaners, porters, receptionists, chefs, and maintenance technicians, who come under the auspices of the Facilities Management (FM) directorate.</p><p> </p><p>It also has 206 people throughout England in FM management roles – including construction projects, health and safety and service delivery.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:33:07.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709360/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709360/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","NHS Property Services: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many staff at NHS Property Services Ltd are employed in a facilities management role.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","66995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709361","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Department commissioned the Royal College of Surgeons (RCS) to set up a cosmetic surgery inter-specialty committee to take forward a number of recommendations made by Professor Sir Bruce Keogh’s review. As part of their work, the RCS committee produced recommendations for a future national audit of cosmetic surgical practice in May 2016, which remain under consideration by the Department.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:32:58.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709361/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709361/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Plastic Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to establish a clinical audit database for cosmetic surgery as recommended by Professor Sir Bruce Keogh's Review of the regulation of cosmetic interventions, published in April 2013.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","66996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709362","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>NHS England holds the contract with Capita for the administration of Primary Care Support Services, including the National Dental Performers List. NHS England has informed us that that it does not hold information on the average turnaround time for applications to join the National Dental Performers List. There is an expectation that applications should take 12 weeks to process but for some applications it can take longer. The Performers List process checks that applicants have the correct evidence to ensure that safeguards are in place for the protection of the public.</p><p> </p><p>Service standards set in the Capita contract are a matter for NHS England as the contract holder. NHS England advises the contract contains a range of remedies to incentivise and address performance. These include the application of financial service credits where agreed levels of performance are not achieved and rectification processes to affect improvement in service performance where this falls below expected levels.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","67033","2017-03-15T16:00:37.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709362/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709362/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Dental Services: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average turnaround time is for applications to the National Dental Performers List since that service has been taken over by Capita.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","67038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709363","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>NHS England is responsible for the provision of primary medical services in England. As such, it is for NHS England to ensure that patients in all areas have access to general practitioner (GP) services. To assess GP service provision in an area and identify future requirements, NHS England works with the Care Quality Commission and local clinical commissioning groups. In terms of overall strategy, the provision of primary care will be part of the Joint Strategic Needs Assessment (JSNA) which is published in each local authority area and reported through the local Health and Well-being Board. The JSNA will identify any gaps and risks in the provision of primary care to the local population which, in turn, will then inform commissioning strategies for that area.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed to an extra 5,000 doctors in general practice by 2020, as part of a wider increase to the total workforce in general practice of 10,000.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-13T15:33:21.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709363/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709363/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","General Practitioners: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has made an estimate of the number of additional GPs that will be required in (a) Coventry and (b) the West Midlands by 2020; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","67065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709364","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>The proposed timescale for the review of the nutrient profiling model is still currently under review and is expected to be published on gov.uk shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The proposed timescales are set to ensure that the options for the review are fully considered through a transparent process and will uphold the latest government recommendations for sugar and fibre.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-15T12:02:01.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709364/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709364/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2017 to Question 62903, what the timescale is for publishing the review of the nutrient profile model; and what the reasons are for the time taken to publish that review.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","67086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709365","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>The number of adult patients seen by a National Health Service dentist in each 24-month period ending from 31 March 2006 can be found in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>The number of children seen by a NHS dentist in each 12 month period ending from 31 December 2015 can be found in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital do not collect data monthly on the number of adults seen by an NHS dentist in each of the last 24 months.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","66938 ; 66939 ; 67081","2017-03-15T14:12:03.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709365/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709365/answer","Number of adult patients aged 18 and over seen in the previous 24 months.docx ; Number of patients aged 0 to 17 seen by an NHS dentist in the previous 12 months.docx","Number of adult patients aged 18 and over seen in the previous 24 months.docx ; Number of patients aged 0 to 17 seen by an NHS dentist in the previous 12 months.docx","PQ66938 attached table 1 ; PQ66938 attached table 2","PQ66938 attached table 1 ; PQ66938 attached table 2","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709365/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Dental Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 February 2017 to Question 63405, how many children were seen by an NHS dentist in the latest 12-month period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","67082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709366","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>We have been provided the following information from Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust regarding investigations relating to employee relations in each of the last three calendar years.</p><p> </p><p>- In 2014, there were 16 investigations relating to employee relations which included six dignity at work investigations and nine grievance investigations. Seven individuals were sanctioned and five employees were dismissed by the Trust as a result of these disciplinary investigations.</p><p>- In 2015, there were 16 disciplinary investigations, which included one dignity at work investigation and nine grievance investigations. Seven individuals were sanctioned and there were no dismissals as a result of these disciplinary investigations.</p><p>- In 2016, there were 21 disciplinary investigations, which included nine dignity at work investigations and six grievance investigations. Seven individuals were sanctioned and one employee was dismissed by the Trust as a result of these disciplinary investigations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:29:39.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709366/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709366/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many investigations relating to employee relations, such as disciplinary grievance and dignity at work cases, have taken place relating to Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust in each of the last three calendar years; and how many of those investigations resulted in (a) sanctions being given and (b) employees being dismissed by that Trust.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","67078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709367","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>Decisions about the provision of bereavement services are best taken locally. It is for local National Health Service organisations to ensure that appropriate facilities and services are in place to support bereaved parents following the death of a baby.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has published <em>Health Building Note 09-02: Maternity Care Facilities</em> a guideline on the design and planning of maternity care facilities in new healthcare buildings and on the adaptation/extension of existing facilities. In line with the guidance, we would expect new build or redesigned maternity units to have facilities available for women and families who suffer bereavement at any stage of pregnancy.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010, we have invested £35 million in the NHS to improve birthing environments and this included better bereavement rooms and quiet area spaces at nearly 40 hospitals to support bereaved families.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016, the Stillbirth and Neonatal Death Charity, Sands, published Audit of bereavement care provision in United Kingdom maternity. The audit found that of the 62 trusts and health boards that responded:</p><p>- 63% has a bereavement room in each maternity unit in the trust or health board;</p><p>- 26% has a bereavement room in at least one maternity unit but not all in the trust or health board; and</p><p>- 11% had no dedicated bereavement room in the trust or health board.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T18:01:08.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709367/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709367/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Maternity Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the (a) number and (b) availability of dedicated maternity bereavement rooms and facilities across the NHS.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","67079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709368","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>The number of adult patients seen by a National Health Service dentist in each 24-month period ending from 31 March 2006 can be found in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>The number of children seen by a NHS dentist in each 12 month period ending from 31 December 2015 can be found in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital do not collect data monthly on the number of adults seen by an NHS dentist in each of the last 24 months.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","66938 ; 66939 ; 67082","2017-03-15T14:12:03.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709368/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709368/answer","Number of adult patients aged 18 and over seen in the previous 24 months.docx ; Number of patients aged 0 to 17 seen by an NHS dentist in the previous 12 months.docx","Number of adult patients aged 18 and over seen in the previous 24 months.docx ; Number of patients aged 0 to 17 seen by an NHS dentist in the previous 12 months.docx","PQ66938 attached table 1 ; PQ66938 attached table 2","PQ66938 attached table 1 ; PQ66938 attached table 2","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709368/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 February 2017 to Question 63405, how many adults were seen by an NHS dentist in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","67081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709369","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>Information relating to the number of midwives to be recruited in the London Borough of Newham and Greater London is not held centrally by the Department.</p><p> </p><p>In the 2016/17 Workforce Plan for England, Health Education England (HEE) estimates the future demand for qualified midwives in England by 2020 will be 24,628.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:50:47.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709369/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709369/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Midwives: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of midwives to be recruited in (a) the London Borough of Newham, (b) Greater London and (c) the UK up to 2020.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","67045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709370","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>The data request is in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCG) and Specialised Commissioning</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£ billion</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>9.60</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>10.08</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>10.81</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Notes:</em></p><ol><li>All figures are given in cash/nominal terms.</li><li>Figures from 2009-2013 are taken from the Department’s accounts and National Health Service programme budgeting data.</li><li>Data for 2013 onwards is from NHS England and relates to CCG and specialised commissioning spend only.</li></ol>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-13T17:58:59.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709370/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709370/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Mental Health Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS and its agencies spent on mental health services in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","67046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709371","Department of Health","false","2017-03-16","<p>There is no specific budget allocated to Individual Funding Requests (IFRs). Approved IFRs are funded through the specialised commissioning budget allocation.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-16T10:30:24.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709371/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709371/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 6 March 2017 to Question 66178, what budget has been allocated to Individual Funding Requests in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","67053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709372","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>This information is not held centrally. Decisions regarding the planning of services in a local area are the responsibility of individual clinical commissioning groups.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-15T15:54:46.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709372/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709372/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Health Services: North East Bedfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to expand health services in North East Bedfordshire to meet growing demand as a result of additional houses being built.","false","Biography information for Alistair Burt","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","67056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709373","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>NHS England holds the contract with Capita for the administration of Primary Care Support Services, including the National Dental Performers List. NHS England has informed us that that it does not hold information on the average turnaround time for applications to join the National Dental Performers List. There is an expectation that applications should take 12 weeks to process but for some applications it can take longer. The Performers List process checks that applicants have the correct evidence to ensure that safeguards are in place for the protection of the public.</p><p> </p><p>Service standards set in the Capita contract are a matter for NHS England as the contract holder. NHS England advises the contract contains a range of remedies to incentivise and address performance. These include the application of financial service credits where agreed levels of performance are not achieved and rectification processes to affect improvement in service performance where this falls below expected levels.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","67038","2017-03-15T16:00:37.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709373/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709373/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Dental Services: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what service standard his Department has set Capita for the average turnaround time for applications to the National Dental Performers List; and what penalties are in place in the event that those standards are not achieved.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","67033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709374","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>Official statistics are published by NHS England on a monthly basis in respect of waiting times for consultant-led referral to treatment waiting times. These statistics provide the length of time from referral through to elective treatment for 18 high volume specialties. This information is published at both provider and commissioner level. Further information can be found at this link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/rtt-waiting-times/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/rtt-waiting-times/</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:35:31.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709374/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709374/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Medical Treatments: Statistics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what statistics (a) his Department, (b) NHS trusts and (c) clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) hold on referrals to treatment by (i) NHS trusts and (ii) CCGs.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","67042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709375","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Department uses the National Health Service performance data published on a monthly basis by NHS England to monitor compliance with waiting times targets for treatment. This information is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/</a></p><p> </p><p>Maintaining waiting time performance is a key objective in the Government’s Mandate to NHS England. Both NHS England and NHS Improvement are providing support and challenge to NHS commissioners and providers to reduce waiting times for hospital treatment.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:37:21.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709375/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709375/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-08","Hospitals: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how his Department monitors compliance with government targets on waiting times for treatment.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","67043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709376","Home Office","false","2017-03-17","<p>The NCA does not hold information on the volume or value of assets which have been restrained, confiscated or subject to civil recovery or property freezing orders by the categories described in the question. The nationality of the individual is not routinely recorded, as it is not always possible to obtain it, and they do not differentiate on the basis of politically exposed persons.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","67001","2017-03-17T11:14:41.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709376/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709376/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Confiscation Orders: Nigeria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) restraint, (b) confiscation, (c) civil recovery and (d) property freezing orders the National Crime Agency has in place in relation to assets belonging to politically exposed persons from Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","67047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709377","Home Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The NCA does not hold information on the volume or value of assets which have been restrained, confiscated or subject to civil recovery or property freezing orders by the categories described in the question. The nationality of the individual is not routinely recorded, as it is not always possible to obtain it, and they do not differentiate on the basis of politically exposed persons. However we have committed to publishing statistics on the use of Unexplained Wealth Orders as outlined in the Criminal Finances Bill.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","67000","2017-04-26T14:49:40.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709377/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709377/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Freezing of Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the value is of assets under restraint of assets related to politically exposed persons in Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","67048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709378","Home Office","false","2017-03-13","<p>Asylum claims made by those who are deaf or hard of hearing are processed in a way that ensures that claimants are not disadvantaged. Where available, officials will use hearing loops, signers or allow the submission of written evidence. Relevant support groups will also be engaged if appropriate.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-13T17:02:26.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709378/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709378/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Asylum: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what additional support her Department provides for people who are deaf and hard of hearing during asylum processes.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","67025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709379","Home Office","false","2017-03-13","<p>Staff are available at visa centres to assist applicants who have a disability (including those who are deaf or hard of hearing). We also encourage applicants who have a disability (or who have accessibility requirements) to bring someone to assist them if needed.</p><p>Furthermore, the new Access UK online application system, which aims to replace all existing paper and online application forms has been developed to support users with access needs, particularly in regards to navigation, compatibility with support tools, content and structure.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-13T17:05:23.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709379/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709379/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Visas: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what additional support her Department provides for people who are deaf and hard of hearing during visa application processes.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","67026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709380","Home Office","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Department’s strategy for the future of the immigration detention estate will be communicated in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-13T17:00:21.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709380/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709380/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Detention Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Oral Answer of 6 March 2017, Official Report, column 561 on immigration: indefinite detention, on what date her Department plans to publish its plan for the future of the immigration detention estate.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","67080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709381","Home Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The NCA does not hold information on the volume or value of assets which have been restrained, confiscated or subject to civil recovery or property freezing orders by the categories described in the question. The nationality of the individual is not routinely recorded, as it is not always possible to obtain it, and they do not differentiate on the basis of politically exposed persons. However we have committed to publishing statistics on the use of Unexplained Wealth Orders as outlined in the Criminal Finances Bill.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","67048","2017-04-26T14:49:40.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709381/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709381/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Confiscation Orders: Nigeria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the value is of assets confiscated by the Government belonging to politically exposed persons from Nigeria since 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","67000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709382","Home Office","false","2017-03-17","<p>The NCA does not hold information on the volume or value of assets which have been restrained, confiscated or subject to civil recovery or property freezing orders by the categories described in the question. The nationality of the individual is not routinely recorded, as it is not always possible to obtain it, and they do not differentiate on the basis of politically exposed persons.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","67047","2017-03-17T11:14:41.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709382/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709382/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Proceeds of Crime: Nigeria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the total value is of recovered assets belonging to politically exposed persons from Nigeria through civil recovery orders by the National Crime Agency since 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","67001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709383","Home Office","false","2017-03-16","<p>Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) is a crime and it is child abuse. The Government will not tolerate a practice that can cause extreme and lifelong physical and psychological suffering to women and girls.</p><p>The police and Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) highlighted that one reason for the lack of investigations and prosecutions is a lack of referrals. In addition, cultural pressures and the age and vulnerability of victims may prevent them coming forward.</p><p>In 2015 we significantly changed the law to break down these barriers. We introduced: extended extra-territorial jurisdiction, lifelong anonymity for victims, a new offence of failure to protect a girl from FGM and a mandatory reporting duty. We have also introduced FGM Protection Orders and latest figures show that 79 have been made to protect girls.</p><p>In addition, the police and CPS have put in place agreed local protocols in all force areas on the investigation and prosecution of FGM. This includes the requirement that prosecutors work closely with the police at the earliest stage possible in providing early investigative advice and helping to identify evidence which will strengthen the case.</p><p>These steps apply to all forces in England and Wales.</p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-03-16T16:11:35.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709383/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709383/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Female Genital Mutilation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to increase the number of prosecutions related to female genital mutilation in (a) Peterborough, (b) Cambridgeshire and (c) England; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","67094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709384","Home Office","false","2017-03-15","<p>Available published data on outstanding appeals can be found in Table S.4 of the Tribunals and gender recognition statistics. These cover the period up to December 2016. The most recent edition is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2016</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-15T17:41:28.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709384/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709384/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Deportation: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many foreign nationals from which countries are appealing against removal proceedings in  (a) the UK, (b) Southend and (c) Rochford and Southend East constituency.","false","Biography information for James Duddridge","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","67150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709385","Home Office","false","2017-03-15","<p>Statistics on persons returned from the UK is published in the Home Office’s <em>Immigration Statistics</em>. The latest edition, <em>Immigration Statistics: October to December 2016</em> is available from GOV.UK on the statistics web pages at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2016</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","67148","2017-03-15T17:39:59.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709385/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709385/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many foreign nationals her Department has started removal proceedings against in (a) the UK, (b) Southend and (c) Rochford and Southend East constituency.","false","Biography information for James Duddridge","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","67147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709386","Home Office","false","2017-03-15","<p>Statistics on persons returned from the UK is published in the Home Office’s <em>Immigration Statistics</em>. The latest edition, <em>Immigration Statistics: October to December 2016</em> is available from GOV.UK on the statistics web pages at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2016</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","67147","2017-03-15T17:39:59.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709386/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709386/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people her Department has deported from (a) the UK, (b) Southend and (c) Rochford and Southend East constituency in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for James Duddridge","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","67148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709387","Home Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>The Home Office does not comment on individual cases.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-21T14:53:44.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709387/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709387/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Deportation: Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2017 to Question 66044, whether her Department holds details of which countries the 40 young people that left care, were referred to in the Department for Education's statistical release entitled Children looked after in England including adoption: 2015 to 2016, published on 28 February 2017, were deported to.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","67099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709388","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-15","<p>Leaving the EU means we will want to take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. Over the coming months we will consult closely with stakeholders to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best help the world’s poorest and deliver value for money for UK taxpayers.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-15T17:49:43.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709388/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709388/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-08","EU Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has for the reallocation of the UK's current contribution to EU development funds after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","67102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709389","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Government set out a firm commitment in the UK Aid Strategy to improve transparency of UK official development assistance. As part of this effort, both the Conflict Stability and Security Fund (CSSF) and the Prosperity Fund will publish online information on programmes during 2017-18.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-14T17:18:34.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709389/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709389/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-08","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, by what date she expects that all projects funded through the (a) Prosperity Fund and (b) Conflict Security and Stabilisation Fund will be listed on her Department's Development project tracker.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","67107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709390","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-14","<p>UK direct financial assistance to the Palestinian Authority is used for the sole purpose of contributing to the salaries of West Bank public servants responsible for providing essential services in the education and health sectors, including both frontline teachers and administrative staff in the Ministry of Education.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-14T17:16:14.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709390/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709390/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-08","Palestinian Authority: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, to clarify how UK aid supports the Palestinian Authority's centralised education service.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","67153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709391","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I provided on 14<sup>th</sup> March 2017 to Question number 66937.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-15T17:53:47.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709391/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709391/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-08","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2017 to Question 64094, if she will publish her Department's review of UK future trade policy.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","67083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709392","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-14","<p>DFID’s work in Nigeria has a major focus on combatting corruption. This includes programmes promoting greater transparency and accountability in Nigeria’s oil and gas sector and work to reduce corruption in local service delivery. A new anti-corruption programme will also support the Nigerian authorities to investigate and prosecute corrupt public officials and work with civil society to raise awareness on corruption. As we step up our work in other countries in the Sahel region, efforts to combat corruption will continue across the region.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-14T17:21:51.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709392/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709392/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-08","Lake Chad Basin: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department is providing to countries in the Lake Chad region to (a) increase the transparency of and (b) reduce corruption in government.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","67034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709393","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-14","<p>Lack of investment and ongoing conflict caused by Boko Haram has contributed to the current humanitarian crisis in the Lake Chad region. Focusing on the North East of Nigeria, DFID is investing in public services, job creation and addressing inequalities. UK support has enabled over 90,000 displaced children to return to school and restored basic health care services for 225,000 people affected by the conflict. As HMG, we are also providing a substantial and increasing package of intelligence, military and development support to the region to tackle Boko Haram.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-14T17:25:03.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709393/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709393/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-08","Lake Chad Basin: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to tackle the root causes of the humanitarian crisis in the Lake Chad region.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","67035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709394","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-14","<p>The UK was one of the first donors to respond to the crisis in the Lake Chad Region. Last year we delivered food assistance to more than 1 million people, and treated 34,000 children at risk of death from severe under-nourishment in North East Nigeria. We have used our funding to encourage others to contribute and are pleased that at the Oslo Donor Conference a number of other countries stepped up their support. The UK is currently examining what further support we can provide in leading the way to help prevent famine in the region.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-14T17:23:08.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709394/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709394/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-08","Lake Chad Basin: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make it her policy to increase the Government's donor contributions to the Lake Chad region to match or exceed those made by other governments at the Oslo donor conference.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","67036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709395","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-14","<p>The UK is committed to supporting children with mental health needs in conflict situations. We use assessments from humanitarian agencies, including the United Nations, to determine how we can best support these vulnerable children.</p><p>The assessments reinforce that psychological trauma amongst children is acute in some of the world’s worst conflicts. In Syria, the annual UN Humanitarian Needs Overview states that 1 in 4 children are at risk of developing mental health disorders. In Iraq, UNICEF judges emotional distress as a critical issue for children fleeing or currently living under Daesh. Afghan children are at risk of psychological distress, particularly in urban areas. On Eritrea, the impact of conflict on children, particularly their mental health needs, continues to be assessed, with UNHCR conducting a thorough assessment of each Eritrean child arriving into Ethiopia.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-14T17:19:38.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709395/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709395/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-08","Developing Countries: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the mental health needs of children fleeing conflict in (a) Syria, (b) Iraq, (c) Afghanistan and (d) Eritrea.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","67054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709401","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-15","<p>On 23 February 2017 we published details of reforms to disincentivise minor, exaggerated and fraudulent personal injury whiplash claims. The Government’s aim is to reduce the high number and cost of such claims.</p><p> </p><p>Measures include a fixed tariff of compensation for whiplash claims with an injury duration of up to two years and a prohibition on offers to settle claims without medical evidence. These will be taken forward in the Prisons and Courts Bill</p><p> </p><p>We will also, through secondary legislation, increase the small claims limit for road traffic accident related personal injury claims to £5,000 and increase the small claims limit for all other personal injury claims to £2,000.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-15T10:30:45.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709401/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709401/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-08","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress has been made on tackling the abuse of personal injury whiplash claims relating to incidents involving motor vehicles.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","67096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709402","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-15","<p>The number of road traffic accident related personal injury claims is over 50% higher than 10 years ago (460,000 in 2005/6 compared with 770,000 in 2015/16). This is despite significant improvements in car safety in recent years and fewer reported road accidents.</p><p>Therefore, the Government has recently consulted on a number of measures to disincentivise not just fraudulent but also minor and exaggerated whiplash claims. An impact assessment setting out the evidence used to assess the impacts of these reforms accompanied this consultation.</p><p>The Government published the first part of its consultation response on 23 February. A revised impact assessment which considers evidence and data supplied by respondents will be published in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-15T17:32:24.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709402/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709402/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-08","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment she has made of trends in the level of fraudulent whiplash claims.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","67077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709403","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-13","<p>The instructions on the external escort of prisoners is set out in Prison Service Instruction 33/2015. This provides comprehensive security procedures to be applied when a prisoner is to be escorted outside the establishment. These procedures are subject to local monitoring and approval. In addition to this, all security compliance is monitored through a central programme of audit and assurance. All serious breaches of security during escort (including prisoner escape) are investigated, and any resulting recommendations carefully considered.</p><p> </p><p>Prisoners are only moved outside the security of the prison when necessary and where the purpose of the escort cannot be met within the prison. The overwhelming majority of escorts pass without incident.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-13T18:05:56.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709403/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709403/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-08","Prisoner Escorts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she is taking to review the level of compliance with prison service instructions on prisoner escort.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","67066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709404","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-15","<p>After the introduction of our two strikes legislation, people caught carrying a knife a second time are now more likely than ever before to go to prison.</p><p> </p><p>The government continues to monitor sentencing for bladed and offensive weapon offences. On 9 March the latest knife possession sentencing quarterly statistics bulletin was published and is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/knife-possession-sentencing-quarterly-brief-october-to-december-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/knife-possession-sentencing-quarterly-brief-october-to-december-2016</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Sentencing Guidelines are produced by the independent Sentencing Council. The Council has developed a draft guideline on sentences for knife possession and threat offences which they consulted on between 6 October 2016 and 6 January 2017. The draft guideline is available from the Sentencing Council’s website: <a href="http://www.sentencingcouncil.org.uk" target="_blank">www.sentencingcouncil.org.uk</a></p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-15T11:22:48.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709404/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709404/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-08","Knives: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of guidelines for tougher sentences for knife crimes on the numbers of people imprisoned for such crimes.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","67064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709405","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-14","<p>A number of meetings relating to whiplash have already been held at both Ministerial and official level with key representative groups and regulators such as the Law Society and the Solicitors Regulation Authority. Ministers and officials will continue to engage with interested parties as the Government moves forward with its reform programme.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-14T17:23:43.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709405/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709405/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-08","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will meet the (a) Law Society and (b) Solicitors Regulation Authority to discuss trends in the number of whiplash claims.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","66986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709406","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-18","<p>I refer my Honourable Friend to the Written Ministerial Statement (<em>Justice update: Written statement - HCWS503</em>) made by my Right Honourable Friend the Lord Chancellor and Secretary of State for Justice on 27 February 2017 and the statement of reasons referred to in it. The statement was laid in the libraries of both Houses and published on the internet at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/discount-rate-summary-of-reasons" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/discount-rate-summary-of-reasons</a>.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-04-18T15:16:59.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709406/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709406/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-08","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reasons she is proposing a negative discount rate for personal injury claims calculations; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","67138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709407","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-20","<p>Question 55553 on prison sentences: Lancashire was answered on 09 March 2017. Question 62826 is not a PQ that was tabled to the Ministry of Justice. The department assumes the hon. Member for Preston was referring to 64826 on Members correspondence which was answered on 15 March 2017, question 64827 on electronic tagging was answered on 16 March 2017. The Secretary of State has responded to the letter on Questions 55553 and 64827 sent by email and post via letter on Friday 17 March 2017.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-20T10:18:59.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709407/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709407/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-08","Ministry of Justice: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she plans to answer Questions (a) 55553 on prison sentences: Lancashire, tabled on 30 November 2016, (b) 62826 on Members: correspondence, tabled on 21 February 2017 and (c) 64827 on electronic tagging, tabled on 21 February 2017 by the hon. Member for Preston; and whether she plans to respond to the letter on Questions 55553 and 64827 sent by email and post by the hon. Member for Preston on 3 March 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","67141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709408","Home Office","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Home Office does not disclose country specific information regarding deportation of foreign national offenders as its disclosure could prejudice relations between the UK and foreign governments.</p><p>The Ministry of Justice publishes data on foreign national offenders imprisoned on a quarterly basis which can be accessed at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/563256/Population_2016.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/563256/Population_2016.xlsx</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-15T17:37:58.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709408/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709408/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-08","Offenders: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many foreign national offenders by country were (a) imprisoned, (b) released from prison and (c) deported in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for James Duddridge","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","67149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709409","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-03-13","<p>The British-Irish Council’s role has not changed following the recent election and its objectives remain to further promote positive, practical relationships among the people of the islands, and to provide a forum for consultation and co-operation.</p><p /><p><br></p><p> </p><p /><p />","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-03-13T16:00:47.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709409/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709409/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-03-08","British Irish Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the role of the British-Irish Council is until the Northern Ireland Executive is restored.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","67146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709410","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-16","<p>a) The data sources, supporting information and assumptions used in Highways England’s traffic modelling have been set out in the Pre-Consultation Scheme Assessment Report which is available on the Lower Thames Crossing public consultation website.</p><p> </p><p>b) The estimate of traffic volumes requested for Option A14 was aggregated in terms of changes in traffic flows across the network, and then compared with other options (including Option C) in terms of overall economic performance. Consequently the breakdown of traffic volumes is not currently held in the form requested. The estimate of traffic volumes for selected links for Option C is reported in the Pre-Consultation Scheme Assessment Report.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-16T11:01:02.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709410/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709410/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Lower Thames Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will (a) set out the data sources, supporting information and the assumptions used and (b) estimate traffic volumes per (i) day and (ii) peak hour for (A) Option A14 and (B) Option C of the Lower Thames Crossing Option on (1) the existing Dartford Crossing, (2) a new Option A14 crossing, (3) a new Option C crossing, (4) the A282 between junction 30 and junction 2 of the M25, (5) the A2 between the M25 and the A227, (6) the A2 between the A227 and the M2, (7) the A227 between the A2 and the A20, (8) the A228 between the M2 and M20 and (9) the A229 between the M2 and the M20.","false","Biography information for Adam Holloway","Gravesham","Adam Holloway","67152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709411","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-14","<p>Any property where the dwelling is situated within the designated Rural Support Zone will meet the location eligibility criteria for this scheme. Due to the complex nature of property boundaries the Department does not hold information on the number of properties where some property, but less than 25% of the total area of the property, is within the Rural Support Zone and so don’t meet the eligibility criteria for this scheme.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-14T14:18:41.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709411/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709411/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many properties situated less than 120 metres away from the proposed line of route for phase 2b of High Speed 2 will not be eligible for compensation because they fail to meet the criterion that at least 25 per cent of the land must be within the designated Rural Support Zone.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","67106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709412","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-13","<p>We have no records of the proportion of speed awareness courses run by public providers rather than private providers. Courses also vary in price across the country. We are therefore unable to say how much money goes into the public purse in any year.</p><p> </p><p>No money from the courses goes into the Consolidated Fund.</p><p> </p><p>The Vehicle Technology and Aviation Bill will, however, lay out in regulations what is being charged, who receives it, and how it is being spent, increasing transparency.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-13T17:40:13.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709412/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709412/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Road Traffic Offences: Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 February 2017 to Question 65327, how much accrued to the public purse in charges for those speed awareness courses under the National Driver Offender Retraining Scheme in (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","67143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709413","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-14","<p>We are looking carefully into the issues raised by the Rees Jeffreys Road Fund report, and recognise that its recommendations are worthy of serious consideration.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-14T14:24:04.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709413/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709413/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Roads","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will respond to the Rees Jeffreys Road Fund report, entitled A Major Road Network for England, published in October 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","66980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709414","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-13","<p>A change in corporate ownership has no impact on the responsibilities of the producer/distributor towards the consumer. Compensation for vehicles affected by a safety recall is a matter for the producer/distributor to agree with the individual consumer. Any Vauxhall vehicle that is currently subject to a safety recall will remain so irrespective of a change in corporate ownership.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-13T17:44:01.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709414/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709414/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Vauxhall Motors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will assess the potential effect of the Peugeot-Citroen deal to buy Vauxhall-Opel on the (a) availability and (b) level of compensation for customers affected by Vauxhall car fires.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","66997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709415","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Department monitors each train operator’s overall performance and there are clear actions set out in the franchise agreement should performance drop below what is expected. This regular monitoring includes monthly meetings between my officials and their senior management where performance figures are scrutinised and challenged.</p><p> </p><p>There are a range of enforcement mechanisms available to the Department in the event of non-compliance.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-03-13T15:02:07.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709415/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709415/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Abellio Greater Anglia: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that Abellio Greater Anglia meets its franchise commitments related to performance; and if he will make it his policy to use his enforcement powers as the franchising authority in the event that those commitments are not met.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","66994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709416","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-17","<p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU, including the implications for the continued participation in the European Aviation Safety Agency system.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-17T09:34:13.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709416/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709416/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","European Aviation Safety Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the costs and benefits of the UK remaining a member of the European Aviation Safety Agency after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","67008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709417","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-16","<p>Option A14 for the Lower Thames Crossing was assessed by Highways England as part of the Options Phase appraisal. The cost-benefit analysis demonstrated that the route would represent poor value for money with a benefit-cost ratio of 0.4.</p><p> </p><p>The appraisal was based on a level of design development and environmental assessment appropriate for the wide range of options considered at this early stage of the project. The cost-benefit analysis uses costs built-up from Highways England’s cost database for UK highways projects, the results of traffic forecasting for this option which include greenhouse gases, accidents, vehicle operating costs, noise, reliability and wider economic impacts and have been measured in line with DfT’s WebTAG guidance. As requested, the cost-benefit analysis will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses shortly.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-16T10:41:58.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709417/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709417/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Lower Thames Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will place the cost-benefit analysis of Option A14 of the Lower Thames Crossing in the Library; and what the data sources and supporting information were for that analysis.","false","Biography information for Adam Holloway","Gravesham","Adam Holloway","67074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709418","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Department is providing £942,875 as requested by Shropshire Council for the development of a business case for this scheme.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-14T14:30:14.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709418/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709418/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Roads: Shropshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding the Government plans to provide to Shropshire Council for developing a business case on the North West Relief Road.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","67087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709419","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-16","<p>Highways England will produce revised traffic volume forecasts as part of the development phase of the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>These forecasts will be informed by data collected from a number of sources, including ANPR cameras and traffic counters. This revised modelling work is expected to be completed in 2018 at the earliest.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-16T10:54:58.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709419/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709419/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Lower Thames Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make a revised estimate of traffic volume forecasts for 2025 and 2041 as published in tables 4.3 and 4.4 of volume 5 of the Lower Thames Crossing Pre-Consultation Scheme Assessment Report, published in January 2016, using information from traffic surveys undertaken since that report was published, including information from ANPR cameras and traffic counters.","false","Biography information for Adam Holloway","Gravesham","Adam Holloway","67097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709420","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-17","<p>Great Western is providing free Wi-Fi on a large majority of their services and Cross Country will be providing this from April 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Our priority is for passengers to experience a reliable and highly available mobile service and we will be securing this within future franchises.</p><p> </p><p>Great Western’s new franchise is due to start from December 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Cross Country’s new franchise is due to start from June 2019.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-03-17T09:30:35.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709420/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709420/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Railways: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made on improving of the reliability and availability of wifi and mobile connectivity on trains between (a) Penzance and London and (b) Taunton and Bristol.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","67011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709421","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-16","<p>The number of times that traffic has been held at the Northbound Dartford Crossing on a red light in order to escort vehicles are as follows;</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Nov-16</p></td><td><p>Dec-16</p></td><td><p>Jan-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2218</p></td><td><p>2184</p></td><td><p>2487</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>This does not count the total number of occasions when escorts occurred. To minimise the number of times necessary to hold traffic to escort vehicles, staff are trained to conduct escorts when traffic is held at red lights by the Traffic Safety System for others reasons e.g. extracting an over height vehicle before it enters the tunnels.</p><p> </p><p>Due to a number of operational activities carried out at the same time as the escort it can be difficult to determine an exact average duration that each escort may take.</p><p> </p><p>However, the majority of escorted dangerous goods vehicles and abnormal loads going through the Dartford tunnels do take less than two minutes on each occasion. A new arrangement is being developed to accurately measure the duration of each crossing and Highways England anticipate making decisions on when new arrangements could become available later this year.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-16T10:37:50.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709421/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709421/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Dartford-Thurrock Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 November 2016 to Question 54114, how many times per month traffic is stopped at the Dartford River Crossing to allow hazardous and oversized vehicles to use the tunnels for each month since November 2016; what the average duration of each such stoppage has been; and when the future work referred to in his Answer will be undertaken to model the potential reduction in the number of escorted vehicles per day.","false","Biography information for Adam Holloway","Gravesham","Adam Holloway","67032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709422","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Government increased the fixed penalty notice for using a hand held phone when driving from 3 to 6 points and £100 to £200 from 1 March 2017.</p><p>We do not plan any further measures until we have evaluated the effectiveness of these new penalties.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-14T14:33:37.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709422/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709422/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-08","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of the introduction of alternative penalties to fines for drivers using mobile telephones.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","67050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709423","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>There will be no cash losers among those who are already in receipt of Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) and we have laid regulations to protect existing ESA claimants, including those who temporarily leave the benefit to try out work and then return to ESA.</p><p> </p><p>The Government published its assessment of the impacts of the change to the work-related activity component on 20 July 2015. <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006B.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006B.pdf</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","67185","2017-03-13T12:43:16.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709423/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709423/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 March 2017 to Question 66433, what estimate he has made of the number and proportion of employment and support allowance work-related activity group claimants who will only be entitled to a reduced rate who will fall below the poverty line as a result of changes in support for that group.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","67041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709424","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-14","<p>We estimate these costs for the removal of the automatic entitlement to housing support for new claims in UC from 18-21 year olds who are out of work to be £3m over the 2015 Spending Review period.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-14T16:01:31.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709424/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709424/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the additional processing and administration costs related to the implementation of the proposed new housing benefit rules for 18 to 21 year olds.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","67018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709425","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>Information on housing benefit claims aged 18 to 21 for the requested periods and by whether in work or not is available on <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/jsf/login.xhtml" target="_blank">DWP Stat-Xplore</a>.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-13T13:35:51.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709425/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709425/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households with claimants aged 18 to 21 were in receipt of housing benefit in (a) 2010-11 and (b) the most recent period for which figures are available; and, of those households, how many received income derived from benefits only in each of those periods.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","67019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709426","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>The information requested is not available. We have recently completed a joint DWP/DCLG consultation on the supported housing model with commissioners and providers, developers and investors, residents and those who represent their views. The new model outlined in our consultation will enable local authorities to assess their provision by utilising their local knowledge to drive transparency, quality and value for money from their service providers.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-13T12:49:43.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709426/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709426/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much top-up funding will be provided to each local authority following the introduction of the Local Housing Allowance cap.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","67090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709427","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>To date no assessment has been made of the effect of a Local Housing Allowance cap that will be introduced in the social rented sector from 2019 on other services provided by local authorities as the policy has not been finalised.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-13T13:05:35.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709427/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709427/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect that a Local Housing Allowance cap will have on other services provided by local authorities.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","67092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709428","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>Local Housing Allowance rates will be introduced into the social rented sector in April 2019. We estimate that this policy will save the Exchequer £235 million in 2019/20.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-13T13:03:04.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709428/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709428/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of implementing the Local Housing Allowance cap.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","67091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709429","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>We do not require details of bank and savings accounts from claimants of contribution-based Employment and Support Allowance (ESA). When individual contribution claims are due to exhaust we invite a claim to income related ESA and if the claimant makes such a claim, we would request details of their household income and capital in order to assess the claim.</p><p> </p><p>We regret that we are unable to provide details of the numbers of these requests without incurring disproportionate costs, as we would have to look at each individual claim affected.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-13T17:34:35.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709429/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709429/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many times his Department has written to claimants of contribution-based employment and support allowance requesting details of bank and savings accounts held in each of the last 12 months; and for what reasons that information was requested.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","67069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709430","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Department has modelled the number of claimants potentially in scope for the policy in Universal Credit based on DWP administrative data on caseload of single 18-21 year olds claimants with no children and no caring responsibilities claiming Housing Benefit and Jobseeker’s Allowance. The proportion of these exempt through being in work for at least the last six months has been estimated using the Family Resources Survey. The proportion exempt because they are vulnerable and/or unable to return to the parental home has been estimated using DWP administrative data on the proportion living in the Social Rented Sector.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-13T13:39:02.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709430/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709430/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what methodology his Department used to estimate how many new claimants will be exempt from the proposed new housing benefit policy for 18 to 21 year olds.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","67003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709431","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>The assessment for Personal Independence Payment (PIP) is designed to treat people as individuals, considering the impact of their impairment or health condition on their everyday life and how each claimant has personally adapted to living with a disability. Since its inception, the system of assessing claimants’ eligibility for PIP has been continually reviewed and refined in order to improve its efficiency and effectiveness. We continue to work extensively with PIP assessment providers and disability representatives to make improvements to guidance, training and audit procedures in order to ensure a quality service is maintained.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-13T12:29:42.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709431/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709431/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of Clause 4, Part 2 of the Social Security (Personal Independence Payment) Regulations 2013.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","66991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709432","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>Information on the caseload of 18-21 year olds claiming Housing Benefit and Jobseeker’s Allowance in the requested areas is available on <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/jsf/login.xhtml" target="_blank">DWP Stat-Xplore</a>.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-13T13:15:26.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709432/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709432/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Housing Benefit and Jobseeker's Allowance: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many 18 to 21 year olds jointly claimed jobseekers support allowance and housing benefit in (a) the UK, (b) Scotland and (c) Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency in each financial year from 2010-11 to date.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","67128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709433","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>Information on Housing Benefit caseloads and average awards for 18-21 year olds for the requested areas and periods is available on <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/jsf/login.xhtml" target="_blank">DWP Stat-Xplore</a>, which multiplied together give expenditure.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-13T13:10:10.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709433/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709433/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the cost to the public purse was of housing benefit expenditure on 18 to 21 year olds for (a) the UK, (b) Scotland and (c) Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency in each financial year from 2010-11 to date.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","67125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709434","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>Information on the caseload of 18-21 year olds claiming Housing Benefit and Employment and Support Allowance in the requested areas is available on <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/jsf/login.xhtml" target="_blank">DWP Stat-Xplore</a>.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-13T13:12:37.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709434/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709434/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Employment and Support Allowance and Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many 18 to 21 year olds jointly claimed employment and support allowance and housing benefit in (a) the UK, (b) Scotland and (c) Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency in each financial year from 2010-11 to date.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","67126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709435","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>The available information for Housing Benefit claims in Great Britain is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p> </p><p>Information for Northern Ireland is the responsibility of the Department for Social Development in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.dsdni.gov.uk/index/stats_and_research.htm" target="_blank">http://www.dsdni.gov.uk/index/stats_and_research.htm</a></p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-13T13:22:45.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709435/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709435/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households claimed housing benefit in (a) the UK, (b) Scotland and (c) Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency in each financial year from 2010-11 to date.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","67127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709436","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>No such estimates have been made. Latest information on the savings from this policy is available in Table 2.2 of Spring Budget 2017 documentation.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-13T13:07:55.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709436/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709436/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-08","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Welfare Delivery of 7 March 2017, Official Report, column 684, on housing benefits, 18 to 21 year olds, how much of the projected savings of £105 million will accrue to the public purse in each region and constituent part of the UK by year.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","67124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709437","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-13","<p>Green Deal Certification Bodies are responsible for certifying Green Deal Installers. A Green Deal Certification Body is required by the Publicly Available Specification (PAS) 2031 to ensure that an Installer company meets both PAS 2030 (the technical standards governing Green Deal installations) for the energy efficiency measures they wish to install and the Green Deal Code of Practice requirements. These cover, among other things, the business and financial probity of the Installer company and the technical competence of individual installers employed by a company.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-13T14:41:05.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709437/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709437/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what account the Green Deal Oversight and Registration Body took of the prior business history of company directors before accrediting Green Deal installers.","false","Biography information for Anne McLaughlin","Glasgow North East","Anne McLaughlin","67140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709438","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Department does not hold information on annual turbine installation rates.</p><p>However, Wind Europe’s “<em>The European Offshore Wind Industry, key trends and statistics 2016</em>” records that, at the end of 2016, the UK had a total of 1,472 turbines installed and connected across 28 windfarms.</p><p>The details can be found at <a href="https://windeurope.org/wp-content/uploads/files/about-wind/statistics/WindEurope-Annual-Offshore-Statistics-2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://windeurope.org/wp-content/uploads/files/about-wind/statistics/WindEurope-Annual-Offshore-Statistics-2016.pdf</a>.</p><p>The Rampion project is in the process of installing the first turbines in the English Channel.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-15T17:54:07.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709438/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709438/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many wind turbines were installed in the (a) Irish Sea, (b) North Sea and (c) English Channel in each year between 2006-07 and 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","67119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709439","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Department does not collate this data on an annual basis. However, the industry currently supports around 13,700 jobs in the UK (7,900 direct and 5,800 indirect) with GVA* of £1 billion (£600m direct and £400m indirect).</p><p> </p><p><em>Source: “The size and performance of the UK low-carbon economy”, BIS, March 2015, </em><em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/low-carbon-economy-size-and-performance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/low-carbon-economy-size-and-performance</a></em></p><p><em>*Gross Value Added</em></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-15T18:01:41.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709439/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709439/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many (a) directly employed and (b) contractor employees there were in the offshore wind industry in each year between 2006-07 and 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","67098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709440","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The table below shows the number of firms that have been removed from the Green Deal (GD) Participants Register each calendar year since the GD scheme began.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Installers Withdrawn by CBs</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>99</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>191</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>410</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>206</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>931</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-21T14:09:43.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709440/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709440/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many firms have been removed from the approved list of Green Deal installers in each calendar year of the scheme to date.","false","Biography information for Anne McLaughlin","Glasgow North East","Anne McLaughlin","67151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709441","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-13","<p>I apologise to the hon. Member. The reply will be sent shortly.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-13T14:32:34.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709441/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709441/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when his Department plans to respond to the letter of 24 January 2017 from the hon. Member for Wolverhampton South West on trades unions' political funds, reference ZA6413.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","67129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709442","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Information Commissioner is the UK's independent authority responsible for administering and enforcing information rights and provides guidance and advice to individuals and organisations on, among other things, the protection of consumer's data.</p><p> </p><p>The Information Commissioner’s Office has a number of tools at its disposal to take action against those that breach the legislation. These powers include the ability to conduct audits, serve enforcement notices and impose civil monetary penalties of up to £500,000.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has announced it would be implementing the forthcoming General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) by May 2018. Amongst other protections offered, the GDPR provides consumers with increased control over how their personal data is processed. This, along with other measures in the GDPR, aims to boost consumer trust in the processing of their personal data.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-14T16:13:16.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709442/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709442/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-08","Consumers: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to improve public trust in the private sector management of consumer data.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","67205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709443","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Data Protection Act 1998 (DPA) covers the processing of personal data. The Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) is responsible for producing guidance for the general public, private and public sector organisations on information rights; this includes informing employees about their information rights and employers about their obligations under the DPA, when it comes to the processing of personal data. The ICO has produced guidance on the processing of employee data, on its website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-data-protection/employment/" target="_blank">https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-data-protection/employment/</a></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-14T16:28:11.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709443/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709443/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-08","Employment: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what her policy is on the ownership of employee data in the workplace.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","67206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709444","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-13","<p>Extended credit terms from suppliers can help businesses to meet their working capital needs, as can prompt payment from customers. While payment terms are a matter for each business to negotiate with their trading partners, the Government is committed to ensuring that all businesses and entrepreneurs across the UK are able to access the finance and support they need to grow and have the right conditions to invest long-term, as set out in the Industrial Strategy Green Paper.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-13T16:02:52.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709444/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709444/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Small Businesses: Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to support small and medium-sized enterprises in accessing extended credit terms.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","66992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709445","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-15","<p>At present, Easter occurs on the first Sunday after the first ecclesiastical full moon following the spring equinox. The Easter Act 1928, which remains on the Statute Book, would set the date for Easter to fall on the Sunday that follows the second Saturday in April (i.e. between 9 and 15 April). The Act has not been brought into force. To do so would require an Order in Council, with the approval of both Houses of Parliament. The Act also requires that, before the Order is made, “regard shall be had to any opinion officially expressed by any Church or other Christian Body.&quot;</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-15T08:49:35.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709445/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709445/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Easter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will take steps to bring into force the provisions of the Easter Act 1928 to fix the date of Easter from 2018 onwards.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","66998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709446","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p>Green Deal Certification Bodies are responsible for certifying Green Deal Installers and monitoring their compliance against the requirements in the Publicly Available Specification (PAS) 2030 and/or Microgeneration Certification Scheme and the Green Deal Code of Practice. The Green Deal Ombudsman and Investigation Service provides a redress path for consumers who have a Green Deal Plan in place and experience problems with the measures installed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-21T13:57:31.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709446/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709446/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Green Deal Scheme: Misconduct","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what responsibility his Department takes for malpractice by accredited Green Deal installers.","false","Biography information for Anne McLaughlin","Glasgow North East","Anne McLaughlin","67075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709447","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-21","<p>Capita, as the scheme administrator for the Green Deal Home Improvement Fund (GDHIF), received information on registered installers from the Green Deal Oversight and Registration Body (GD ORB), which managed the authorisation scheme for participants. A company was listed on the GDHIF Register if it was on the Green Deal Register.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-21T14:23:03.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709447/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709447/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what criteria were used to draw up the list of approved installers under the   Green Deal Home Improvement Fund.","false","Biography information for Anne McLaughlin","Glasgow North East","Anne McLaughlin","67076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709448","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-16","<p>National Grid, as System Operator, is responsible for recommending a target capacity for Capacity Market auctions. This recommendation is based on National Grid’s assessment of different scenarios for the level of electricity demand and takes account of projected changes in electricity use. National Grid’s recommendation is scrutinised by an independent Panel of Technical Experts before my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy decides on the final target.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-16T15:39:15.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709448/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709448/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709448/answer/previousversion/40358","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether capacity market auctions take into account future growth projections for electric vehicles.","false","Biography information for Graham Stringer","Blackley and Broughton","Graham Stringer","67030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709449","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-16","<p>The Government has set out its ambition for almost all cars and vans to be zero emissions by 2050. By setting a long-term target, the Government is seeking to ensure that there is time to ready the grid for the mass transition towards cleaner, more efficient vehicles. Existing mechanisms, such as the Capacity Market and network operator business planning, can be used to ensure that network and generating capacity will stay in step with growing electric vehicle demand. Through further work to increase the flexibility in electricity demand and supply, including through promoting smart charging, we aim to ensure that electric vehicle demands are managed efficiently.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-16T15:35:17.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709449/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709449/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709449/answer/previousversion/40360","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has undertaken to ensure the capacity of the electricity grid to respond to current and future demand for electric vehicles.","false","Biography information for Graham Stringer","Blackley and Broughton","Graham Stringer","67031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709450","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Department works closely with the Department for Education (DfE) which is responsible for skills policy and also the Construction Industry Training Board (CITB), the body that supports training and skills in construction.</p><p>DfE is currently working with employers in the construction industry to develop new apprenticeships for the sector. While evidence suggests there are sufficient learners going through the skills system, with over 200,000 construction qualifications being taken each year, reforms set out in the skills plan (July 2016) will ensure these qualifications become more relevant and better meet the industry’s needs.</p><p>In addition, the Construction Leadership Council (CLC), the business led sector council which advises Government on key strategic issues, has investigated the labour model in construction and commissioned an independent report from Mark Farmer (published in October 2016):</p><p><a href="http://www.constructionleadershipcouncil.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Farmer-Review.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.constructionleadershipcouncil.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Farmer-Review.pdf</a>.</p><p>We will set out shortly how we are taking forward the report’s recommendations with the CLC.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-03-14T16:40:01.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709450/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709450/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-08","Construction: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent steps he has taken to address the national skills gap in the construction industry.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","67040"
