"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708907","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-13","<p>Advice from HM Treasury officials to ministers was released on 30 September 2016 in response to a Freedom of Information request. The advice provides background to the decision to exclude energy generation as a qualifying activity in the venture capital schemes and Social Investment Tax Relief (SITR). The advice, dated 15 October 2015, stated that around 200 community energy schemes had registered in the year to September 2015. Of the 200, 72 were community benefit societies, and the remainder were community interest companies. Co-operative societies were not included in this analysis because they do not qualify for SITR investment.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-13T17:18:01.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708907/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708907/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-07","Community Interest Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many of the community interest companies referred to in the advice given by Treasury officials to Ministers in preparation for the Autumn Statement of 2015 as indicated by the response to the Freedom of Information request to a member of Community Energy England dated 30 September 2016 (reference R52/16) are (a) community benefit societies and (b) co-operative societies.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","66834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708908","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-13","<p>Buildings occupied by the vast majority of public bodies, including local authorities, have been subject to non-domestic rates since they were introduced in 1990. This is part of delivering a fair and consistent system of non-domestic rates.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-13T17:14:58.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708908/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708908/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","Non-domestic Rates: Public Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 64309, on non-domestic rates: public bodies, if he will grant public bodies the same rate relief as that granted to charities.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","66855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708909","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-23","<p>My Department has operated a small number of unpaid work placements in each of the last five years. Almost all of these placements arise from cross-Whitehall internship and Department for Work and Pensions led movement to work schemes.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total Unpaid Placements</p></td><td><p>Total placements lasting more than one month</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-23T16:04:00.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708909/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708909/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","Department for Communities and Local Government: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708910","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-15","<p>Statutory guidance to the Building Regulations in<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/approved-documents%20" target="_blank"> Approved Document A <em>Structure</em></a> states that wall ties should be made of stainless steel (which is considered to be corrosion resistant) and have a minimum embedment length in each wall leaf of 50mm.</p><p>The Department has not issued any guidance to home owners, as identification, investigation and specifying repairs of corroded wall ties are specialist technical matters that are best left to a structural engineer or building surveyor. It is also likely that the building insurer will be involved.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-15T16:27:45.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708910/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708910/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","Housing: Corrosion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department has issued for home owners on the risk of wall tie corrosion.","false","Biography information for Craig Williams","Cardiff North","Craig Williams","66865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708911","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government and the Department for Work and Pensions work closely together to ensure that our policy priorities are aligned. The two departments are in regular contact at ministerial level.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-15T16:26:58.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708911/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708911/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","Homelessness: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on the potential effect of ending the automatic entitlement to housing benefit for 18 to 21 year-olds on levels of homelessness.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","66779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708912","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy provides core funding to Citizens Advice, the umbrella body for the local Citizens Advice service in England and Wales. That core funding allows for the provision of essential central services to the network including IT, information, training and the recruitment of volunteers and the auditing of bureaux to ensure they retain their capability and capacity to deliver.</p><p> </p><p>Central Government does not fund individual Citizens Advice offices (formerly referred to as bureaux) who receive funding from a variety of public, charity and private sources, with core funding typically provided by the Local Authority in which they are located.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-15T15:32:27.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708912/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708912/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-07","Citizens' Advice Bureaux","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will assess the adequacy of the level of Government funding for Citizens Advice services; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","66780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708913","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-26","<p>Government’s capital expenditures on affordable housing through government’s affordable homes programmes are available publicly.</p><p>A summary of housing expenditure under the Housing Corporation for the period 2000 - 2008 and the National Affordable Homes Programme 2008-11 is available through the National Archives website:</p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20071204140632/http:/www.housingcorp.gov.uk" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20071204140632/http://www.housingcorp.gov.uk</a></p><p>For the Affordable Homes Programme 2011-2015:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/affordable-homes-programme-2011-to-2015-guidance-and-allocations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/affordable-homes-programme-2011-to-2015-guidance-and-allocations</a></p><p>For the Affordable Homes Programme 2015-2018:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2015-to-2018-quarterly-updates" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2015-to-2018-quarterly-updates</a></p><p>For the Shared Ownership and Affordable Homes Programme 2016-21:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2016-to-2021-successful-bidders" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2016-to-2021-successful-bidders</a></p><p>Data for London only is available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.london.gov.uk/about-us/london-assembly/london-assembly-committees/budget-monitoring-sub-committee" target="_blank">http://www.london.gov.uk/about-us/london-assembly/london-assembly-committees/budget-monitoring-sub-committee</a></p><p><a href="https://www.london.gov.uk/about-us/governance-and-spending/spending-money-wisely/annual-accounts-and-governance-statement" target="_blank">https://www.london.gov.uk/about-us/governance-and-spending/spending-money-wisely/annual-accounts-and-governance-statement</a></p><p>Information on expenditure on affordable housing prior to 2000 is not publicly available.</p><p>Between 1997 and 2010 social housing stock fell by 420,000. Since 2010 the overall stock of social housing has increased by 76,000.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-26T14:50:37.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708913/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708913/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the net capital expenditure on affordable housing by the Homes and Communities Agency and its predecessor agencies was in each year since 1991-92, by region.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","66913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708914","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-16","<p>The Government has put in place a £3.6 billion package of transitional relief to help businesses facing an increase following revaluation. The Budget on 8 March included a further package to support business. £110 million will be available to assist rate payers, including eligible rural businesses losing rural rate relief as a result of revaluation. In addition, the Government is making available a £300 million discretionary relief fund over the next four years to enable local authorities to help individual businesses that are having difficulties paying increased rates bills.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-16T09:23:33.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708914/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708914/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","Non-domestic Rates: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to mitigate the effect of increases in business rates on rural business in the tourism and hospitality industry.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","66909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708915","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-13","<p>Details of the transitional relief scheme are set out in the Government's response to the consultation on this issue available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/572823/Transitional_Relief_consultation_response.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/572823/Transitional_Relief_consultation_response.pdf</a></p><p>This provides a regional breakdown of the scheme, including for the West Midlands. Details of the scheme below the regional level are not available.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","67133","2017-03-13T17:12:27.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708915/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708915/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","Non-domestic Rates: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 64310, on non-domestic rates, (a) how much and (b) what proportion of the transitional relief scheme funding will be allocated to (i) the West Midlands and (ii) Birmingham.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","66955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708916","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-13","<p>Transitional relief is automatically applied to business rates bill by the relevant billing authority. It is not necessary for local authorities to apply for transitional relief funding.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-13T17:09:19.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708916/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708916/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 64310, on non-domestic rates, whether local authorities will have to apply for funds from the transitional relief scheme.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","66956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708917","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-13","<p>I will deposit these documents in the Library of the House.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-13T17:15:27.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708917/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708917/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","Planning: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to his letter of 16 July 2015 to Joanne Demetrius of Veolia ES (UK) Ltd, reference APP/M1900/V/13/2192045, if he will place in the Library copies of documents (a) VES/11/1 - Proof of Evidence - Steven Kosky - Planning, (b) VES/11/2 Summary to Proof of Evidence - Steven Kosky - Planning, (c) VES/11/3 Appendices to Proof of Evidence - Steve Kosky - Planning and (d) VES/11/4 Supplementary Proof of Evidence - Steven Kosky - Planning.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","66944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708918","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-13","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my answer on 3 March 2017 to Question UIN 64254 which explains the Commission's assessment of our application.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-03-13T17:06:20.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708918/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708918/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","European Union Solidarity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 3 March 2017 to Question 64254, on the European Union Solidarity Fund, what the costs involved in making an application were; and what each constituent element of those costs were.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","66947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708919","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-13","<p>Under the Housing (Right to Manage)(England) Regulations 2012 (RTM) the following notice proposals (applications) were served and accepted by local authorities thereby initiating the statutory process.</p><ul><li><p>2014 – No RTM proposal notices served.</p></li><li><p>2015 – 3 RTM proposal notices served and accepted by local authorities; 2 by the London Borough of Southwark; and 1 by the London Borough of Enfield</p></li><li><p>2016 – 3 RTM proposal notices served and accepted by local authorities; 1 each from the London Boroughs of Lambeth, Southwark and Barking and Dagenham.</p></li></ul><p>These regulations cover England only.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-13T17:13:10.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708919/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708919/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-07","Right to Manage Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many Right to Manage applications were approved in each of the last three years by each local authority area in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","66962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708920","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-13","<p>Ofcom does not have such an estimate. Levels of investment by BT in its Openreach network will be considered as part of Ofcom’s forthcoming Wholesale Local Access market review consultation.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-13T14:25:22.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708920/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708920/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-07","Broadband: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 February 2017 to Question 64364, on broadband: infrastructure, if she will ask Ofcom or British Telecom to estimate the amount of copper line (a) laid and (b) refurbished by British Telecom in those years.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","66949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708921","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-13","<p>We set out the representations that had been received in the oral statement the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport gave in the House of Commons on Monday 6th March. Hansard of the debate can be found following this link:</p><p>https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2017-03-06/debates/045187F9-4209-47B1-B7B9-BA1AD6473DCE/Sky21StCenturyFoxProposedMerger#debate-240030</p><p> </p><p>Representations received since then are being assessed and an update will be given in the week commencing 13th March.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-13T16:59:02.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708921/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708921/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-07","21st Century Fox: Sky","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what representations she has received on the proposed merger between 21st Century Fox and Sky.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","66922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708922","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-13","<p>Media payments are a commercial matter for racing and betting and we do not hold specific figures relating to individual Licensed Betting Offices (LBOs). Payment of the Horserace Betting Levy is based on gross profits and not directly linked to the number of LBOs.</p><p> </p><p>On 7 March we laid a Statutory Instrument to reform the current Levy. This includes extending its scope to betting operators based offshore that are selling to consumers in Britain. This will ensure a level playing field for betting operators that are based in Britain and offshore operators, and increase funding for racing.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-03-13T12:44:47.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708922/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708922/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-07","Betting Shops: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the financial effect on the horse racing industry of one betting shop closing on (a) media and (b) levy payments.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","66805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708923","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-14","<p>The UK Digital Strategy published on 1st March sets out that for the UK to be a world-leading digital economy that works for everyone, it is crucial that everyone has the digital skills they need to fully participate in society. Through the Digital Skills Entitlement we will ensure that adults who lack core digital skills can access specified basic digital skills training free of charge where it is made available as part of the publicly funded adult education offer. In the meantime the Government continues to support adults to improve their basic digital skills, both through funding through the Adult Education Budget for education providers to offer digital training as part of their education offer, and an additional programme with The Good Things Foundation that aims to educate adults with the very basic skills needed to be able to search confidently and safely online and access public services. Additionally to support the launch of the UK digital strategy, industry pledged to create more than 4 million new free digital skills training opportunities adding to a range of existing digital skills offers some of which were set out in the UK Digital Strategy.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-14T16:25:17.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708923/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708923/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-07","Digital Technology: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate her Department has made of the number of people without the basic digital skills referred to in the report of the Science and Technology Committee, Digital Skills Crisis, HC 270, published on 13 June 2016, who will be able to access the measures announced in part two of her Department's 2017 Digital Strategy.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708924","Department for Education","false","2017-03-13","<p>Ada, the National College for Digital Skills, is being set up to deliver the higher level technical skills needed by the sector. The College opened to its first group of students in September 2016, and once fully operational is expected to attract learners from across the country. Funding is being made available from a range of sources, including Advanced Learner Loans. The Government also announced in the March 2017 Budget that maintenance loans for adults undertaking higher-level technical education at level 4+ will be made available for learners attending National Colleges from the 2019/20 academic year.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-13T11:32:38.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708924/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708924/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","Ada, National College for Digital Skills: Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what financial support is available to students from outside London to support them in attending courses at the National College of Digital Skills.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708925","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-14","<p>Barefoot offers free teaching-resources and volunteer-led training workshops, designed to help primary school teachers get more confident when teaching computer science and computing skills. Barefoot is UK wide, and more than 1 million primary school children have benefitted from this training so far, and a further 500,000 will be reached by the end of the 2017/18 academic year.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-14T16:24:05.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708925/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708925/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-07","Digital Technology: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the potential geographical spread of the training referred to on page 9 of part two of her Department's Digital Strategy 2017 to be offered through the Barefoot Computing Project; and of what that training will consist.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708926","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Department’s annual local bus survey collects information on the local bus sector in Great Britain, including on passenger numbers, mileage and vehicle fleet. However, no information on the number of bus services which provide on-board WiFi is currently collected as part of the survey.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-13T17:50:47.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708926/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708926/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-07","Bus Services: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of bus (a) franchises and (b) services which provide onboard WiFi.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708927","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-13","<p>The legislation to underpin the new digital entitlement is being progressed as part of an amendment to the digital economy bill. Further timescales will be set out in due course. The Government continues to support adults to improve their basic digital skills, both through the Adult Education Budget for education providers to offer digital training as part of their education offer, and an additional programme with The Good Things Foundation that aims to educate adults with the very basic skills needed to be able to search confidently and safely online and access public services, which has supported 680,000 people since 2014.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-13T17:01:10.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708927/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708927/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-07","Digital Technology: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 5 of part two of her  Department's 2017 Digital Strategy, when the programme to ensure that adults who lack core digital skills can access specified basic digital skills training free of charge will be rolled out.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708928","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-14","<p>We have made no such estimate.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-14T13:13:03.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708928/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708928/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-07","Digital Technology: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the report of the Science and Technology Committee, Digital Skills Crisis, HC 270, published on 13 June 2016, what estimate her Department has made of the current requirement for additional workers to fill the digital skills gap.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708929","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to Question 56303 from the hon. Member for Sheffield, Heeley (Louise Haigh), on 12 December 2016.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-03-09T16:09:11.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708929/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708929/answer","20161216_56303_MOD_Work_Experience (1).pdf","20161216_56303_MOD_Work_Experience (1).pdf","56303 - MOD Work Experience","56303 - MOD Work Experience","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708929/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-07","Ministry of Defence: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708930","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-13","<p>The provision of quality accommodation to our Service personnel is of the utmost importance and is at the heart of the Armed Forces Covenant. Currently around 94% of UK Service Family Accommodation (SFA) some 46,230 properties are at the Decent Homes standard or above. Only SFA at those standards will be allocated to new occupants. Through the Ministry of Defence's (MOD) Single Living Accommodation (SLA) Modernisation (SLAM) project and other projects some 54,000 bed spaces have been delivered across the estate at over 52 locations. The MOD is developing a new SLA management infrastructure system to provide more accurate data on SLA condition, scale and utilisation. This will enable more effective and consistent management and allocation of SLA, and allow the MOD to target its investment more effectively on sites where we have a long-term requirement.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-03-13T17:15:11.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708930/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708930/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-07","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the quality of (a) service accommodation and (b) service family accommodation.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","66809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708931","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-14","<p>The War Pensions Scheme (WPS) and the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme (AFCS) are two entirely separate schemes. The WPS provides no fault compensation to former Service personnel and their dependants for injuries and death as a result of service before 6 April 2005. The AFCS provides compensation for injury, illness or death caused by service in the UK Armed Forces on or after 6 April 2005. It is therefore not possible for a veteran in receipt of benefits under the WPS to transfer to the AFCS for injuries caused in service prior to 2005.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-03-14T16:35:38.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708931/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708931/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-07","Armed Forces Compensation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of permitting veterans in receipt of benefits under the War Pension Scheme, as a result of injuries received in service prior to 2005, to transfer to the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","66776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708932","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-13","<p>No UK military technical support or advice is being provided to the UAE for coalition military operations in Yemen.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-03-13T17:18:12.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708932/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708932/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-07","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what UK military technical support or advice is being provided to the UAE for coalition military operations in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","66964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708933","Department for Education","false","2017-03-28","<p>The estimated costs of a closure form only one element of a decision, which will take into consideration both the risks involved and dependencies required to deliver each of the options, and the best and most sustainable strategy for delivering good or outstanding school places for every child in the local area.</p><p>Releasing details of estimated closure costs could make factors that are equally influential in the arguments for and against closure seem less significant and give a misleading picture as to how the decision was made. The primary objective of the department in making such decisions is to secure value for money for the taxpayer whilst ensuring the best possible educational outcomes for the pupils and parents.</p><p>Releasing details of estimated closure costs would not provide a complete picture of the situation. In some cases, those details may also be commercially sensitive. The primary objective of the Department in making such decisions is to ensure the best possible educational outcomes for the pupils and parents whilst also securing value for money for the taxpayer.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-28T16:38:12.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708933/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708933/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","Baverstock Academy: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 20 February 2017 to Question 63407, on Baverstock Academy: closures, for what reason her Department does not provide financial information on the estimated cost of proposed school closures when an academy is consulting on whether to close.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","66940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708934","Department for Education","false","2017-03-13","<p>The number of pupils, with a full age breakdown, in every school, is published in the underlying data of the statistical publication available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-13T09:28:16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708934/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708934/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","Primary Education: Pupils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of pupils in (a) reception, (b) KS1 and (c) KS2 attend an (i) infant, (ii) junior and (iii) a middle school in the current school year.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","66861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708935","Department for Education","false","2017-03-13","<p>Guidance for head teachers on the process for considering whether pupils should be entered for end of Key Stage statutory assessments is provided in the ‘2017 Assessment and Reporting Arrangements’ for Key Stage 1 and Key Stage 2. This was published by the Standards and Testing Agency in October 2016.</p><p> </p><p>These documents set out the statutory requirements for National Curriculum assessment and reporting for the 2016 to 2017 academic year. They make it clear that the responsibility for making the final decision about whether it is appropriate for an individual pupil to be entered for statutory assessments resides with that pupil’s head teacher. The head teacher should report their decision to the pupil’s parents.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-13T09:31:40.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708935/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708935/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","National Curriculum Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidance is issued to head teachers by her Department on parent withdrawal of a child from statutory assessments.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","66862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708936","Department for Education","false","2017-03-16","<p>The Department is investing over £24bn in school buildings from 2016- 2021 to maintain schools, rebuild and replace buildings in the worst condition, and ensure there are enough school places in the system. This includes over £10 billion allocated for maintaining and improving the condition of the school estate from 2016-2021.</p><p>Hampshire County Council received £19,367,940 in school condition allocations in 2015-16 and £19,370,943 in 2016-17 which allows them to make localised decisions to address their individual priorities such as maintaining the condition of their school estate. These are indicative of the allocation Hampshire will receive in 2017-18, which will be announced shortly. These figures do not include school condition allocations to multi-academy trusts with schools in Hampshire.</p><p>While this funding is not aimed specifically at SCOLA schools, it is allocated using a formula which takes into account data on the condition of school buildings gathered through the Property Data Survey.</p><p>The Department is updating its information on the condition of the school estate through the Condition Data Collection, which will provide information on areas of the highest condition need and drive our approach on how we invest in order to target them.</p><p>Schools in Hampshire have also received £5,009,333 in devolved formula capital in 2016-17. Fifteen academies in Hampshire also bid successfully for funding through the Condition Improvement Fund last year. We expect to announce successful projects in this year’s CIF round by April 2017.</p><p>Six schools in Hampshire are included in the £4.4 billion Priority School Building Programme aimed at rebuilding or refurbishing those school buildings in the very worst condition across the country.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-16T17:37:58.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708936/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708936/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","Schools: Hampshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if the Government will provide more support for Hampshire County Council to cover the building condition liabilities of the Second Consortium of Local Authorities schools in that county.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","66871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708937","Department for Education","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Department continues to work closely with Ofqual, the exam boards and key sector bodies to communicate to key audiences the changes to GCSEs, including the new 9-1 grading scale.</p><p>In July 2016, the Department and Ofqual jointly produced a slide pack that was sent to all schools in England to help teachers prepare and explain the changes to parents and pupils.</p><p>Ofqual has also issued a series of short videos and social media activities for a variety of audiences including parents.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-13T11:40:13.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708937/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708937/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department has taken to help parents of school-age children understand the new numerical GCSE grading system.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","66951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708938","Department for Education","false","2017-03-13","<p>We will base the decision on whether to extend the Returners Engagement Programme pilot on an assessment of its success at helping teachers find teaching positions. The first cohort started training last month and we are working with the partnered schools to improve and develop the programme further for a second cohort to start training in May. A decision to continue will be taken by September.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-13T09:26:08.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708938/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708938/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","Teachers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 6 March 2017 to Question 64894, on teachers: recruitment, what plans her Department has to extend the Returners Engagement Programme pilot to other parts of the country.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","66958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708939","Department for Education","false","2017-03-13","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>I would refer the honourable member to my response to PQ60334 which I have laid out below:</p><p>Statistics on the average salaries of teachers employed by schools and local authorities in England are published in Tables 9a to 9d of the ‘School Workforce in England: November 2015’ statistical release which is available at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2015</a></p><p>The figures show that the average salary for all full and part-time teachers is £37,800.</p><p>The latest data, for November 2015, shows the average salary for a full-time teaching assistant is £19,200.</p><p>The Department’s pay reforms have given schools greater flexibility to decide how much to pay their teachers and how quickly their pay progresses over time.</p><p>Future salaries of teachers will be informed by the annual recommendations of the School Teachers Pay Review Body. The pay of teaching assistants and school support staff are set by schools themselves. The Department does not produce forecasts of future average pay for these staff.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-13T09:25:07.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708939/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708939/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","Teachers: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average unit cost was to a (a) school and (b) local authority of employing a teacher in 2015-16; and what estimates she has made of such costs in (i) 2016-17, (ii) 2017-18, (iii) 2018-19 and (iv) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","66945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708940","Department for Education","false","2017-03-15","<p>For reasons of commercial confidentiality and to ensure that the department and the free school proposers are able to maintain strong bargaining positions during negotiations, capital costs are not disclosed before costs are finalised. Capital funding for open free schools, UTCs and studio schools where costs have been finalised are published on Gov.UK at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-funding-for-open-free-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-funding-for-open-free-schools</a>. The final capital costs Future Tech Studio in Warrington have not yet been published but are due to be included in the next publication round in coming months.</p><p>The revenue costs are publish online as follows -</p><p>Schools block funding allocations are published on Gov.UK. The link for Pre 16: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-block-funding-allocations-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-block-funding-allocations-2016-to-2017</a> and post 16 Data: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/16-to-19-education-funding-allocations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/16-to-19-education-funding-allocations</a>.</p><p>Pre and posting open grant allocations for studio schools are published on Gov.UK at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/revenue-spending-on-open-and-withdrawn-utcs-and-studio-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/revenue-spending-on-open-and-withdrawn-utcs-and-studio-schools</a></p><p>Pupil premium: allocations and conditions of grant are published on Gov.uk at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/pupil-premium-information-for-schools-and-alternative-provision-settings" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/pupil-premium-information-for-schools-and-alternative-provision-settings</a>.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-03-15T16:45:29.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708940/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708940/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","Further Education: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the (a) capital and (b) revenue costs of the Future Tech Studio in Warrington.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","66935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708941","Department for Education","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p> </p><p>Requests for unpaid work experience placements are handled by individual business units and no record is kept of them.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-14T15:45:28.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708941/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708941/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708941/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","Department for Education: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in her Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708943","Department for Education","false","2017-03-13","<p>As part of their legal duties in relation to exclusion, schools must have regard to the statutory guidance issued by the Department for Education. Parents approaching the Department with concerns about an exclusion are informed about the formal routes of challenge available to them and directed to sources of free and impartial advice. If the Department identified that a governing body had acted unlawfully or unreasonably in carrying out its legal duties, and it would be expedient to so, then the Secretary of State could issue a direction. The Department would also pass to Ofsted any relevant evidence that fell within the inspectorate’s remit.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-03-13T11:44:07.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708943/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708943/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","Pupil Exclusions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, who has primary responsibility for investigating reports of possible illegal school exclusions.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","66856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708944","Department for Education","false","2017-03-14","<p>There are 3 university technical colleges (UTC) due to close in August 2017 – Daventry UTC, UTC Lancashire and Greater Manchester Sustainable UTC.</p><p>In addition, UTC Tottenham will cease to be a UTC and will become a 16-19 free school, London Academy of Excellence Tottenham.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-14T16:31:53.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708944/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708944/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","University Technical Colleges: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many university technical colleges are due for closure.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","66847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708945","Department for Education","false","2017-03-14","<p>The number of students enrolled at university technical colleges (UTC) in each of the last 5 years can be found in the penultimate document of the underlying data at the following links:</p><p> </p><p>2016</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/532042/SFR20_2016_Underlying_Data.zip" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/532042/SFR20_2016_Underlying_Data.zip</a></p><p> </p><p>2015</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/434186/SFR16_2015_Underlying_Data.zip" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/434186/SFR16_2015_Underlying_Data.zip</a></p><p> </p><p>2014</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/406916/SFR15_2014_Underlying_data_v102.zip" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/406916/SFR15_2014_Underlying_data_v102.zip</a></p><p> </p><p>2013</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/207734/SFR21-2013_UD.zip" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/207734/SFR21-2013_UD.zip</a></p><p> </p><p>2012</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/167515/sfr10-2012ud.zip" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/167515/sfr10-2012ud.zip</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>January 2017 census data will be published in summer 2017 and will include UTCs which opened in September 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Capacity data for each UTC is taken from published funding agreements and can be found in the attached spreadsheet.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-14T16:29:03.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708945/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708945/answer","66848 attachment.xlsx","66848 attachment.xlsx","Annex 1","Annex 1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708945/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","University Technical Colleges: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, (a) what the full capacity is of and (b) how many students have been enrolled in each university technical college in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","66848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708946","Department for Education","false","2017-03-16","<p>As last week’s Budget demonstrates, the Government is determined to ensure every child has access to a good school place and is given the opportunity to fulfil their potential.</p><p>The best university technical colleges (UTC) are providing excellent technical and professional education. We are strengthening the UTC programme to make it more sustainable, including partnerships with successful secondary schools, establishing more UTCs as part of multi-academy trusts, and doing more to raise parent and pupil awareness.</p><p>Three UTCs have closed after opening whilst a further UTC, Royal Greenwich, ceased to be a UTC and became an 11-18 secondary school in September 2016.</p><p>The capital and pre-opening revenue expenditure for each of the closures is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>UTC</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Capital costs</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Revenue costs</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Black Country UTC</p></td><td><p>£2,423,504</p></td><td><p>£742,070</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hackney University Technical College</p></td><td><p>£3,292,754</p></td><td><p>£470,793</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Central Bedfordshire UTC</p></td><td><p>£6,408,488</p></td><td><p>£363,088</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-16T17:38:14.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708946/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708946/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","University Technical Colleges: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much has been spent on the opening of university technical colleges that have since been closed.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","66849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708947","Department for Education","false","2017-03-16","<p>The Government ran a market testing process with a cross-section of potential investors in the student loan book from the end of September into November 2016. This sought feedback on potential sale structures and key features of the transaction and informed the design of the sale. This was a commercial rather than a public process and was conducted under non-disclosure agreements. We do not intend to publish a report of the details. Protecting the details of the conclusions of market testing will help the ongoing sale process achieve value for money for taxpayers.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-03-16T12:34:25.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708947/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708947/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 65006, on students: loans, if she will publish details of the in-depth market testing exercise.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","66851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708948","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-14","<p>An independent study published in 2013 to identify and assess the impacts and risks associated with sky lanterns suggested that the risks to animals or damage to the environment by sky lanterns were relatively minor, and reported that voluntary action and initiatives have been shown to be effective.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Any action we take must be proportionate to the level of risk. An outright ban would be disproportionate in the circumstances, so across government, we have been taking forward a series of non-regulatory measures aimed at minimising the risks associated with sky lanterns and driving up safety standards. Local Authorities are also using existing powers to restrict or regulate the use of lanterns on council-owned land.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-14T13:13:08.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708948/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708948/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-07","Sky Lanterns","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will bring forward legislative proposals to regulate the use of sky lanterns to protect livestock on farms; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","66864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708949","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-21","<p>Defra does not retain details centrally on the number of work placements in the Department and to identify the information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-21T11:41:35.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708949/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708949/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-07","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in her Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708950","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Environment Agency does not develop policy, however, operational staff throughout the Environment Agency routinely give advice and guidance to operators on end of waste matters. The Environment Agency also has a Definition of Waste team, consisting of four staff members, with specific expertise on end of waste alongside other responsibilities in waste regulation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are other non-operational and legal experts in the Environment Agency who provide advice on end of waste matters as part of their wider responsibilities.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-14T10:46:28.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708950/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708950/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-07","Waste Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many officials in the Environment Agency are working on end of waste policy and programmes.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","66868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708951","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Environment Agency has developed several different mechanisms to support businesses in determining whether products are waste or not. These include end of waste frameworks (Quality Protocols) for thirteen different waste streams, a self-assessment web tool ‘IsItWaste’, and published data on comparator non-waste materials. All support tools can be found on the ‘<a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/turn-your-waste-into-a-new-non-waste-product-or-material" target="_blank">turn your waste into a new non-waste product</a> or material’ page on GOV.UK. Defra has also produced guidance on the legal definition of waste, also available on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Businesses seeking support on achieving end of waste status for their products can also contact their local Environment Agency office for further advice and guidance.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-14T10:58:25.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708951/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708951/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-07","Business: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what support her Department provides to businesses on the process for achieving end of waste status for their products.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","66920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708952","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-14","<p>In the last five years, no Environment Agency staff members have been employed by Defra to work on end of waste policy and programmes.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-14T11:05:17.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708952/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708952/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-07","Waste Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many officials in the Environment Agency have been employed by her Department to work on end of waste policy and programmes in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","66921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708953","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-13","<p>Since 1 January 2016, 1,729 claimants have received payments of around £50 million which were made outside the Basic Payment Scheme 2015 window which runs between 1 December 2015 and 30 June 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","66880","2017-03-13T17:16:53.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708953/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708953/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-07","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the number of delayed individual payments which were not paid within the Basic Payment Scheme payment window since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","66863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708954","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-13","<p>During the January 2017 air pollution episode, Defra issued daily tweets from the UK-Air Twitter account, which provided information about current air pollution levels and accompanying health advice. These included details of the affected regions and links to regionalised maps. These are routinely retweeted by Public Health England and are followed by journalists who use the information to inform their reporting, as well as health charities and campaign groups who regularly retweet information to vulnerable populations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra also issued a press release on 23<sup>rd</sup> January, which was updated on 24<sup>th</sup> January. This provided details of the episode, including the affected regions and health advice targeted both at the general population and vulnerable people.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra also alerted its network of health charities. These alerts provided full details of the nature of the air pollution episode, its geographical location and anticipated duration and links to further information including specific health advice relevant to the episode. The health charities network includes the British Lung Foundation (BLF), who used social media (Twitter and Facebook) to communicate the information, along with the BLF’s own health advice, to their subscribers and patient support groups.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","66924","2017-03-13T10:58:35.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708954/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708954/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-07","Air Pollution: Lung Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department took (a) nationally and (b) in Bristol to ensure that people with a lung condition were aware of how best to protect their health during the high pollution episodes in January 2017.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","66923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708955","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-13","<p>During the January 2017 air pollution episode, Defra issued daily tweets from the UK-Air Twitter account, which provided information about current air pollution levels and accompanying health advice. These included details of the affected regions and links to regionalised maps. These are routinely retweeted by Public Health England and are followed by journalists who use the information to inform their reporting, as well as health charities and campaign groups who regularly retweet information to vulnerable populations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra also issued a press release on 23<sup>rd</sup> January, which was updated on 24<sup>th</sup> January. This provided details of the episode, including the affected regions and health advice targeted both at the general population and vulnerable people.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra also alerted its network of health charities. These alerts provided full details of the nature of the air pollution episode, its geographical location and anticipated duration and links to further information including specific health advice relevant to the episode. The health charities network includes the British Lung Foundation (BLF), who used social media (Twitter and Facebook) to communicate the information, along with the BLF’s own health advice, to their subscribers and patient support groups.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","66923","2017-03-13T10:58:35.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708955/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708955/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-07","Air Pollution: Lung Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department took to (a) ensure that schools and nurseries had information on how to protect children's lungs and (b) notify hospitals to ensure that they were on alert for respiratory patients during the high pollution episode in January 2017.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","66924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708956","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>Exposure to short-lived air pollution episodes (over a few days or weeks) has been associated with increases in respiratory and cardiovascular disease events, potentially leading to increased risk of mortality and hospitalisation, and exacerbation of conditions, such as asthma.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England looked at the impact of two air pollution episodes (related to particulate matter, PM2.5) over a 10-day period in March and April 2014 (Macintyre et al., 2016). It was found that the total burden of emergency hospital admissions for respiratory and cardiovascular causes associated with short-term exposure to PM2.5 was estimated to be around 1,500 across the United Kingdom (around 3.5% of total emergency respiratory and cardiovascular hospital admissions). Around 785 of these would be expected from more typical pollution levels at this time of year.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-13T10:01:57.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708956/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708956/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the contribution of air pollution to the increased incidence of hospital admissions for respiratory conditions over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","66925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>We will be following the legislative process on the proposed constitutional amendment closely. The UK recognises the genuine threat from terrorism which Bahrain faces. We continue to work closely with the Government of Bahrain to encourage progress on human rights, which includes building effective and accountable institutions, strengthening the rule of law, and police and judicial reform. We continue to encourage Bahrain to live up to its international and domestic human rights obligations.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T16:35:12.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708957/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Bahrain: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the effect of the proposed constitutional change in Bahrain to allow military courts to try civilians on human rights in that country.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","66908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708959","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-15","<p>​As NATO allies, the UK and Turkish governments regularly discuss military activity in the Aegean Sea, particularly NATO operations.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-15T17:34:53.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708959/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708959/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Turkey: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations the Government has made to the Turkish Government on recent military activity in the Aegean Sea.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","66910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708960","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office and our Embassy in Bahrain are monitoring this issue closely. The Ministry of Interior Ombudsman has responsibility for investigating allegations of mistreatment in detention. We encourage all those with concerns about their treatment in detention to report these directly to the Ombudsman, and we urge the Ombudsman to carry out thorough investigations into any such allegations. We also continue to encourage the Government of Bahrain to deliver on its international and domestic human rights commitments. We continue to raise concerns about human rights with the Bahraini authorities both in private and in public.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T16:32:33.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708960/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708960/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Sayed Alwadaei","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations the Government has made to the Bahrainian Government on the detention of members of Sayed Alwadaei's family in that country.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","66907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708961","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-13","<p>The United Kingdom remains extremely concerned about the persecution and discrimination of religious minorities in Iran. Our statement during the interactive dialogue with the Special Rapporteur on the Situation of Human Rights in Iran will reiterate our serious concerns about the treatment of the Baha'is and freedom of religion in Iran.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-13T14:40:05.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708961/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708961/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Iran: Baha'i Faith","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will instruct the UK Mission to Geneva to raise a question on the situation of the Baha'is in Iran with the Special Rapporteur on Iran, Ms Asma Jahangir, during her interactive dialogue with member states at the 34th session of the Human Rights Council; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","66859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708962","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-15","<p>​The UK and the EU are pursuing a comprehensive approach, addressing the root causes and consequences of migration. The Malta Declaration, which followed the Valletta Informal European Council in February, sets out areas where the EU can collectively help address the rising number of refugees and migrants crossing the Central Mediterranean. We also remain committed to working with our European partners to ensure that the EU-Turkey Statement is implemented in an effective and sustainable way.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-15T17:31:13.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708962/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708962/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Europe: Migration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking in consultation with other EU member states to discourage migrants from travelling to Europe by sea.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","66936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708963","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-13","<p>The human rights situation in Iran is deeply worrying. The UK fully supports the Iran resolution at the Human Rights Council and will co-sponsor. We have been actively lobbying in favour of the resolution and have consistently called on Iran to allow access to the Special Rapporteur so she can carry out her important work.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-13T14:41:40.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708963/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708963/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Iran: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether it is his policy for the UK to co-sponsor a resolution renewing the mandate of the Special Rapporteur on Iran at the 34th session of the Human Rights Council; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","66860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708964","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>​We are seeking clarification from the Israeli Government on the potential impact on British nationals.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T16:36:37.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708964/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708964/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Israel: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications for British citizens of new legislation in Israel preventing the granting of entry permits, visas and residency rights to foreign nationals supporting a boycott of Israel and the Israeli settlements.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","66919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708965","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>We are closely following the situation in the North West and South West regions of Cameroon following on from the demonstrations and strikes by lawyers and teachers. We are engaged with the Government of Cameroon and will continue to raise the internet blackout with them.</p><p>We have called for restraint by all involved, and have petitioned the government to restore the internet as soon as possible. We have reiterated the obligation to uphold human rights standards and encouraged the use of transparent legal means to address concerns. We have regularly called for issues to be resolved through dialogue, with a range of interlocutors, and a return to normality in the two regions.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T17:01:05.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708965/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708965/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Cameroon: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Government of Cameroon on internet access in that country.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","66797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708966","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>I have not yet had the opportunity to meet my counterpart in the Cameroonian Government but hope we can meet when our diaries allow. I know that the FCO and our High Commissioner is in regular contact with President Biya and his administration.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T17:04:07.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708966/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708966/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Cameroon: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he last met his counterpart in Cameroon; and what issues were discussed at that meeting.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","66798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708967","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-15","<p>All those who undertook work experience at the FCO between 2012-2016 were paid an allowance, except:</p><ul><li>The four participants on the Movement to Work Scheme in 2016, who each continued to receive their benefits during their two-week placement</li><li>The two participants on a one-week Civil Service Work Experience (CSWE) placement in 2016. Participants received an advance payment to cover their travel and lunch costs</li><li>15 Social Mobility Interns between 2012-2015 on a two-week residential work experience programme. Participation was free and interns received an advance payment to cover meal and travel costs.</li></ul>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-15T17:32:49.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708967/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708967/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708968","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>Approximately 130,000 of the 36 million visitors to the UK in 2015 were Nigerians visiting for business and leisure purposes. The World Bank reports 600,000 total visitors to Nigeria in 2013; there is no available data on how many of these were from the UK. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is not involved in discussions to promote tourism between Nigeria and the UK.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T17:09:37.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708968/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708968/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Nigeria: Tourism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had on tourism between Nigeria and the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","66814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708969","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>Officials frequently engage with local diaspora groups. The Nigerian diaspora in the UK are an incredible human resource, who bring expertise, knowledge, education, experience and entrepreneurial skills that can be deployed creatively to benefit Nigeria's future development and prosperity.</p><p>A recent example of our engagement with the Nigerian diaspora was through a roundtable discussion in Manchester on Modern Slavery with community and faith leaders in February 2017. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has previously hosted similar discussions on a variety of issues including prosperity.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T17:11:20.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708969/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708969/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Nigeria: Emigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions his Department has had with representatives of the Nigerian diaspora in the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","66815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708970","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Government's discussions with the Nigerian government on energy continue to focus on increasing production and transmission in-country to tackle the energy deficit which is undermining economic development.</p><p>There have not been any Government to government discussions on how to enable Nigerian energy suppliers to supply the UK.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T17:14:11.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708970/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708970/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Nigeria: Energy Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions the Government has had with the Nigerian Government on enabling Nigerian energy suppliers to supply the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","66816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708971","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>I have not had any such discussions with the Iranian government. It is for Iran to decide the process for the Presidential election and we encourage the Iranian authorities to fulfil their obligations under the International Covenant on Civil and Political rights.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T16:30:27.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708971/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708971/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Iran: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Iranian Government on enabling reconciliation with the Green Movement before the presidential election in that country.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","66811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708972","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>Environmental degradation in the Niger Delta has had a devastating impact on the environment and communities of the region. I was able to see this first hand when I visited the Delta in September 2016. I have encouraged the Nigerian government to take action on tackling oil spills in the region, including by implementing the UN Environment Programme's recommendations on the Ogoniland clean-up.</p><p>Our High Commission in Abuja is in regular contact with officials from the Ministry of Environment, working to strengthen the Nigerian government's regulatory response and increase accountability for environmental damage.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T17:07:28.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708972/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708972/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Nigeria: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions the Government has had with the Nigerian Government on tackling environmental damage to the Niger Delta.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","66812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708973","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>We are concerned about the sentencing of Pastor Hassan Abduelraheem Kodi and Mr Abdulmonem Abdumawlla, who must be given the opportunity to take up their right to appeal. We regularly raise this case with the Sudanese authorities; most recently the UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan did so with senior figures of the Government of Sudan during his visit to Khartoum between 6-8 March.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T17:16:58.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708973/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708973/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Hassan Abduraheem Kodi Taour and Abulmonem Abdulmawla","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the Sudanese authorities to support the appeal of the sentences of Sudanese pastor Reverend Hassan Abduraheem and Darfuri student Abulmonem Abdulmawla.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","66845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708974","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-14","<p>Senior officials in both Khartoum and London continue to raise the importance of freedom of religion or belief as part of our human rights dialogue with the Government of Sudan. We urge the government to uphold the commitment to their citizens in the Interim Constitution of 2005, within which religious freedom is enshrined.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-14T17:18:38.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708974/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708974/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-07","Sudan: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Sudanese authorities on the treatment of religious minorities in Sudan.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","66846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708975","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>Information is not held centrally on NHS England’s total spend on special care dentistry or the number of people with learning disabilities accessing special care dentistry.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","66839","2017-03-13T15:39:32.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708975/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708975/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Special Care Dentistry: Learning Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of people with learning disabilities accessing special care dentistry in England in the latest period for which figures are available.","true","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","66840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708976","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>Currently, the Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency only regulates dermal fillers that are placed on the United Kingdom market as medical devices, as defined in the Medical Devices Regulations 2002. The majority of these products are intended to be used in reconstructive surgery, and as a result they are considered to be medical devices.</p><p> </p><p>The conformity of medical devices in general is approved by independent certification organisations called 'Notified Bodies'. As a result, medical devices are CE marked (rather than ‘approved’ or licenced), and a manufacturer is obliged to obtain a CE mark for their product via a Notified Body.</p><p> </p><p>Dermal fillers come within the highest risk classification in the Medical Device Directive and as such, the manufacturer must be able to provide evidence of the safety, quality and performance of their product before they are granted a CE mark by the Notified Body and allowed on to the market.</p><p> </p><p>Medical devices cannot be designated as “prescription only”, as this term only applies to medicinal products. The Government currently has no plans to introduce such a category for medical devices.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-15T11:50:18.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708976/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708976/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Plastic Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans the Government has to reclassify dermal fillers as prescription only medicines.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","66850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708977","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>Information is not held centrally on NHS England’s total spend on special care dentistry or the number of people with learning disabilities accessing special care dentistry.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","66840","2017-03-13T15:39:32.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708977/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708977/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Special Care Dentistry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much NHS England spent on special care dentistry in the most recent financial year for which figures are available.","true","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","66839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708978","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>The information requested is not available. It is not possible to identify corrections to, or complications from, previous cosmetic surgery in Hospital Episodes Statistics data.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:40:07.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708978/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708978/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Plastic Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many procedures the NHS carried out to correct cosmetic surgery or resolve complications resulting from such surgery in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","66853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708979","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Government published a consultation on 22 August 2016 on the scope of performance assessment of providers regulated by the Care Quality Commission. This included proposals to apply performance ratings to additional provider sectors, including cosmetic surgery providers. The document is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/547103/Scope_of_CQC_ratings_Con_Doc_A.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/547103/Scope_of_CQC_ratings_Con_Doc_A.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>It is our intention to extend performance ratings to this sector by October 2017.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:38:21.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708979/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708979/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Plastic Surgery: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to require the Care Quality Commission to rate providers of cosmetic surgery.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","66854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708980","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>We welcome the development of new drugs and treatments for people with different stages of dementia. However, there needs to be further research and evidence about the effectiveness of magnetic brain-training therapy, NeuroAD, before it can be considered for potential use by the National Health Service.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-15T13:43:59.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708980/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708980/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Alzheimer's Disease: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make the magnetic brain-training therapy, NeuroAD, available on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","66802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708981","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>All bereaved parents should be offered the same high standard of care and support in an appropriate environment.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016, the Stillbirth and Neonatal Death Charity, Sands, published <em>Audit of bereavement care provision in UK maternity.</em> The audit found that of the 66 trusts and health boards which responded, 62% of the maternity units they cover have at least one bereavement support midwife that is based there.</p><p>NHS England has commissioned Sands to undertake a project on the role of the bereavement midwife. The project will make recommendations for the remit of the role of the bereavement midwife and also give some guidance on the support structures required around the role. Sands are due to report their finds to NHS England later this year.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:39:59.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708981/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708981/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Maternity Services: Bereavement Counselling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the level of bereavement support midwife availability in maternity units across the NHS.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","66829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708982","Department of Health","false","2017-03-13","<p>All bereaved parents should be offered the same high standard of care and support in an appropriate environment.</p><p>In 2016, the Stillbirth and Neonatal Death Charity, Sands, published <em>Audit of bereavement care provision in UK maternity. </em>The audit found that of the 69 trusts and health boards responding to the survey 91% reported that each of the maternity units they covered have access to at least one cold or cuddle cot.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-13T17:39:18.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708982/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708982/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Maternity Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the level of cold cot availability in maternity units across the NHS.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","66830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708983","Department of Health","false","2017-03-14","<p>My Rt hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health has not met one to one with the Chief Executive of the Professional Standards Authority.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-14T16:23:47.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708983/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708983/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Professional Standards Authority for Health and Social Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he last met the Head of the Professional Standards Authority; what was discussed at that meeting; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Tredinnick","Bosworth","David Tredinnick","66810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708984","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Department does not hold central records on the number of people undertaking unpaid work placements in the Department.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-15T13:40:27.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708984/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708984/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Department of Health: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708985","Department for Education","false","2017-03-15","<p>Exemptions from the Immigration Skills Charge for employers were announced on 24 March 2016. These include exemptions for employers of specified occupations skilled to PhD level and individuals switching from a Tier 4 student visa to Tier 2 (General). All employers, including the NHS, who recruit workers through the Tier 2 skilled worker route will benefit from these exemptions.</p><p> </p><p>We have not estimated the potential annual cost of the charge to providers. The cost will depend on employer use of the Tier 2 skilled worker route. The Government has no plans to reimburse the cost of the Immigration Skills Charge for any employer.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","66866 ; 67154","2017-03-15T16:51:18.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708985/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708985/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-07","NHS: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will estimate the cost of the immigration skills charge to providers in financial year 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","66867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708986","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>As insurability under European Union law is not determined on the basis of nationality, it is not possible to provide information on the reimbursement costs under EU Regulations 883/2004 and 987/2009, and Directive 20011/24 under the European Health Insurance Card, S1 and S2 scheme. Other Economic European Area (EEA) countries and Switzerland reimburse the United Kingdom for the cost of the National Health Service providing treatment to people they are responsible for under EU law, including UK nationals insured in another EEA country or Switzerland, irrespective of nationality.</p><p> </p><p>The following table provides information on the numbers of S2 forms issued.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p>Financial years April-March</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>S2/E112</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Out-going</p></td><td><p>1,442</p></td><td><p>1,312</p></td><td><p>1,354</p></td><td><p>1,355</p></td><td><p>1,330</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Overseas Healthcare Team (OHT), Department for Work and Pensions (DWP)</p><p>Note: It is possible that issued S2s to customers have not been used</p><p> </p><p>Information on S2 arrangements approved retrospectively is not available.</p><p> </p><p>The following table provides information on the numbers of S1 forms registered by individuals in Foreign Authorities (FA) for whom the UK is responsible under the EU law.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p>Registration In Financial Years April-March</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Registered by FA</p></td><td><p>7,561</p></td><td><p>19,887</p></td><td><p>46,412</p></td><td><p>28,600</p></td><td><p>25,198</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: OHT, DWP</p><p>Note: Data is from 1 April to 31 March</p><p> </p><p>Data above includes forms issued E106, E109, E120, E121, E122 and S1, these exclude PRC, E123, DA1, E112 and S2.</p><p>Timeline of data</p><p>2011 to 2012</p><p>OHT moved to Washington and staff training started. There were low skill levels in this period.</p><p>2013</p><p>OHT had a back log of work which was taken on and cleared by staff in Porth.</p><p>2014</p><p>Registrations start to level out.</p><p> </p><p>The following list provides information on how many European Health Insurance Cards were issued in the last five years:</p><p> </p><p>2015-16 6,069,233</p><p>2014-15 5,414,977</p><p>2013-14 5,571,060</p><p>2012-13 5,240,608</p><p>2011-12 6,830,734</p><p>Source: NHS Business Services Authority</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","66794 ; 66795 ; 66874","2017-03-15T17:26:57.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708986/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708986/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-07","Health Services: Reciprocal Arrangements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many applications for treatment under S2 arrangements were approved retrospectively in each of the five financial years preceding 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Lord Lilley","Hitchin and Harpenden","Mr Peter Lilley","66796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/708987","Department of Health","false","2017-03-15","<p>As insurability under European Union law is not determined on the basis of nationality, it is not possible to provide information on the reimbursement costs under EU Regulations 883/2004 and 987/2009, and Directive 20011/24 under the European Health Insurance Card, S1 and S2 scheme. Other Economic European Area (EEA) countries and Switzerland reimburse the United Kingdom for the cost of the National Health Service providing treatment to people they are responsible for under EU law, including UK nationals insured in another EEA country or Switzerland, irrespective of nationality.</p><p> </p><p>The following table provides information on the numbers of S2 forms issued.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p>Financial years April-March</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>S2/E112</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Out-going</p></td><td><p>1,442</p></td><td><p>1,312</p></td><td><p>1,354</p></td><td><p>1,355</p></td><td><p>1,330</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Overseas Healthcare Team (OHT), Department for Work and Pensions (DWP)</p><p>Note: It is possible that issued S2s to customers have not been used</p><p> </p><p>Information on S2 arrangements approved retrospectively is not available.</p><p> </p><p>The following table provides information on the numbers of S1 forms registered by individuals in Foreign Authorities (FA) for whom the UK is responsible under the EU law.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p>Registration In Financial Years April-March</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Registered by FA</p></td><td><p>7,561</p><